opf]]\n| Baja Ridge\n| Moderate (Maximum with VR Goggles.)\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Riders careen through steep banking turns and spirals in and out of the treetops.  Revolution has a full 360 degree loop which is the first modern vertical loop in the world. In 2016 the coaster received a major renovation which included: new trains, lapbars, new paint job, new lighting, reduced foliage and VR Goggles were added to intensify the ride.\n|-\n| [[The Riddler's Revenge]] \n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Riddler's Revenge 1.JPG|150px]]\n| 1998\n| [[Bolliger & Mabillard]]\n| Metropolis\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Upon opening, it was the tallest, fastest, longest stand-up coaster in the world. Riders traverse six inverted turns over the course of its {{convert|4370|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} track.\n|-\n| [[Road Runner Express (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Road Runner Express]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:Road Runner Express - Six Flags Magic Mountain.JPG|150px]]\n| 2011\n| [[Vekoma]]\n| Bugs Bunny World\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Junior roller coaster.\n|-\n| [[Scream (roller coaster)|Scream]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM-_Scream.jpg|150px]]\n| 2003\n| [[Bolliger & Mabillard]]\n| Screampunk District\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Floorless trains riding above the rails traverse seven inversions on {{convert|3985|ft|m}} of steel track.\n|-\n| Speedy Gonzales Hot Rod Racers\n|{{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Speedy Gonzales Roller Coaster.jpg|150px]]\n| 2014\n| [[Zamperla]]\n| Bugs Bunny World\n| Mild\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Race-car themed [[Zamperla]] family gravity coaster with helix.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hometownstation.com/santa-clarita-news/arts-and-entertainment/magic-mountain/six-flags-magic-mountain-announces-new-ride|title=Six Flags Magic Mountain Announces New Ride Speedy Gonzales Hot Rod Racers|publisher=KHTS AM 1220|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221205236/http://hometownstation.com/santa-clarita-news/arts-and-entertainment/magic-mountain/six-flags-magic-mountain-announces-new-ride|archivedate=February 21, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Superman: Escape from Krypton]] \n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM-Superman Escape from Krypton.JPG|150px]]\n| 1997\n| [[Intamin]]\n| Samurai Summit\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | First coaster to reach 100&nbsp;mph. Riders accelerate in reverse from 0 to {{convert|104|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} in seven seconds and climb nearly 41 stories into the air. Entrance to Superman: Escape from Krypton, a launch roller coaster. Known in the past as \"Superman: The Escape\" (1997\u20132010).\n|-\n| [[Tatsu]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:Six Flags Magic Mountain Tatsu2.jpg|150px]]\n| 2006\n| [[Bolliger & Mabillard]]\n| Samurai Summit\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Upon opening, Tatsu was the tallest, fastest, and longest flying roller coaster in the world. Suspended beneath a steel track, riders experience a total of {{convert|263|ft}} in elevation changes while harnessed in a prone position. It also features the world's largest pretzel loop.\n|-\n| [[Twisted Colossus]]\n|{{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Twisted Colossus.jpg|150px]]\n| 2015\n| [[Rocky Mountain Construction]]\n| Screampunk District\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Riders experience steep drops, banking curves, and two inversions on nearly {{convert|5,000|ft|m}} of track - designed to pit two simultaneously operating trains in a race against each other. It is also the world's longest racing coaster.\n|-\n| [[Viper (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Viper]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Viper.JPG|150px]]\n| 1990\n| [[Arrow Dynamics]]\n| Baja Ridge\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{convert|188|ft|m}} tall with seven inversions reaching speeds up to {{convert|70|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}\n\n|- \n| [[West Coast Racers]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:Six Flags Magic Mountain - 49256408391.jpg|150px]]\n| 2020\n| [[Premier Rides]]\n| The Underground\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Quadruple launch racing coaster, In partnership with [[West Coast Customs]].\n|-\n| [[X2 (roller coaster)|X\u00b2]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:X2-firstdrop.jpg|150px]]\n| 2002\n| [[Arrow Dynamics]]\n| Baja Ridge\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Riders experience predetermined forward and reverse somersaulting maneuvers while harnessed in seats that pitch on a separate axis from the track. Known in the past as \"X\" (2002\u20132007). It was the world's first 4D coaster.\n|}\n\n===Other attractions===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n! Ride\n! Picture\n! style=\"width:7%;\"| Year Introduced\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Manufacturer\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Location in Park\n! style=\"width:5%;\"|Thrill/Intensity Rating\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Description\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Buccaneer\n| {{N/A|}} [[File:SFMM- Buccaner.jpg|150px]]\n| 1980\n| [[Intamin]]\n| Goliath Plaza\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Swinging pirate ship ride.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Pacific Speedway\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Cyclone 500.jpg|150px]]\n| 1992\n| J & J Amusements\n| The Underground\n| Mild\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Go-Kart attraction. Requires nominal fee for participation.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Dive Devil\n| {{N/A|}}\n| 1996\n| [[SkyCoaster|SkyCoaster Inc.]]\n| The Underground\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Large swing attraction simulating the experience of sky diving. Requires nominal fee for participation.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| The Flash Speed Force\n| {{N/A|}}\n| 1974\n| [[Mack Rides]]\n| DC Universe\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Mack Musik Express ride known in the past as Himalaya from 1974\u20131986; Subway from 1987\u20131993, ACME Atom Smasher from 1994\u20132004, and Atom Smasher from 2005\u20132010.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Wonder Woman Lasso of Truth\n| {{N/A|}}\n| 1974\n| [[Hrubetz]]\n| DC Universe\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| First known as Electric Rainbow between 1974 and 1986, then Turbo between 1987 and 1993, then Gordon Gearworks between 1994 and 1998 and finally Grinder Gearworks between 1998 and 1999.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Grand Carousel \n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Grand Carousel 2.JPG|150px]]\n| 1971\n| [[Philadelphia Toboggan Coasters]]\n| Six Flags Plaza\n| Mild\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| A merry-go-round called PTC #21 with origins beginning in 1912. It was removed in the 1960s from the Savin Rock Amusement area in [[West Haven, Connecticut]] and sold to Magic Mountain. Grand Carousel is a family friendly ride located in the Six Flags Plaza area.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Jet Stream (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Jet Stream]] \n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Jet Stream 1.JPG|150px]]\n| 1972\n| [[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow Development]]\n| The Underground\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Flume ride. First Arrow flume to use a turntable loading system. Known from 2001\u20132006 as Arrowhead Splashdown. Jet Stream is a family friendly flume ride located near the entrance to Gold Rusher. The ride opened in 1972.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Justice League: Battle for Metropolis]]\n| {{N/A|}} [[File:SFMM- Justice League Battle for Metropolis.jpg|Justice League Battle for Metropolis|150px]]\n| 2017\n| [[Sally Corporation]]\n| Metropolis\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align;\"| An interactive 4D shooting family dark ride.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Lex Luthor: Drop of Doom]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:Lex Luthor, Drop of Doom - Six Flags Magic Mountain.JPG|150px]]\n| 2012\n| [[Intamin]]\n| Screampunk District  \n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Free fall drop thrill ride from a height of {{convert|400|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}, attaining a terminal velocity of {{convert|85|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. It was the tallest drop tower until 2014 when Zuminjaro: Drop of Doom opened.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Honda Express\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Orient Express.JPG|150px]]\n| 1971\n| Korneuberg Shipbuilding Company ([[Austria]])\n| Six Flags Plaza / Samurai Summit\n| Mild\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{RailGauge|1000mm|allk=on}}<ref>{{Cite web|title=Trams of the World 2017|url=http://blickpunktstrab.net/wordpress2/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/tramsderwelt2017.pdf|publisher=Blickpunkt Stra\u00dfenbahn|date=January 24, 2017|accessdate=February 16, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216202427/http://blickpunktstrab.net/wordpress2/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/tramsderwelt2017.pdf|archivedate=February 16, 2017}}</ref> [[funicular]] railway ride, which transports guests to Samurai Summit next to Ninja.  Repainted in 2016 to blue/white in conjunction with Honda sponsorship. Previously known from 1988 - 2016 as Orient Express and from 1971\u20131988 as ''Funicular''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecoasterguy.com/index.php/2011/10/17/ride-profile-orient-express/|title=Ride Profile: Orient Express|author=Kurt Dahlin|accessdate=February 8, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Roaring Rapids]]\n| [[File:SFMM- Roaring Rapids 2.JPG|150px]]\n| 1981\n| [[Intamin]]\n| Rapids Camp Crossing \n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Rapids water attraction simulating a wilderness raft expedition. Roaring Rapids at Six Flags Magic Mountain. Many guests claim it is the best water ride at the park.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Jammin' Bumpers\n| {{N/A|}}\n| 1971\n| [[Reverchon]]\n| BoardWalk\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Bumper cars.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Scrambler\n| [[File:SFMM- Scrambler.JPG|150px]]\n| 2003\n| [[Eli Bridge]]\n| BoardWalk\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| The park's former old Scrambler was damaged from an uprooted tree. This Scrambler was relocated from [[Six Flags Over Texas]].\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Sling Shot\n| {{N/A|}}\n| 2012\n| [[Funtime (manufacturer)|Funtime]]\n| The Underground\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Sling Shot extra charge attraction.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Swashbuckler\n| [[File:SFMM- Swashbucker.jpg|150px]]\n| 1983\n| [[Chance Rides]]\n| Goliath Plaza \n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Chance Yo-Yo attraction.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Tidal Wave (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Tidal Wave]] \n| [[File:SFMM- Tidal Wave 02.JPG|150px]]\n| 1989\n| [[Intamin]]\n| BoardWalk\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Shoot-the-Chute]] flume. Goes under a bridge on which people get soaked. Tidal Wave is a Shoot the Chute water ride which features a {{convert|50|ft|m|1|adj=on}} drop. The ride is labeled by Six Flags Magic Mountain as a family friendly ride.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|CraZanity \n| [[File:SFMM- Crazinity.jpg|Crazanity|150px]]\n| 2018\n| [[Zamperla]]\n| BoardWalk \n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| A Zamperla Giga Discovery. Pendulum ride. {{convert|172|ft|m}} high. {{convert|75|mph|km/h}}. Tallest pendulum ride in the world.\n|}\n\n==Former rides & attractions==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:16%;\"|Ride\n! style=\"width:7%;\"|Year Opened\n! style=\"width:7%;\"|Year Closed\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Manufacturer\n! style=\"width:65%;\"|Description\n|-\n|99 Steam Train\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1981\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Crown Metal Products]]\n|The {{RailGauge|2ft|lk=on}} [[Narrow gauge railway|narrow gauge]] train ride to Trollywood, the troll country.<ref>[http://www.steamlocomotive.com/lists/searchdb.php?str=Calgrove+Kennels&country=USA Surviving Steam Locomotive Search - Calgrove Kennels]</ref>\n|-\n|Billy the Squid\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1973\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Anton Schwarzkopf]]\n|[[Octopus (ride)|Polyp Ride]]. In 1973 this Polyp ride had a maintenance problem and was removed. The Jolly Monster was built on its site.\n|-\n|Circus Wheel\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1999\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Chance Rides]]\n|Chance [[Wipeout (ride)|Trabant]] with Roman theming. It spun in a clockwise direction and tilted at the same time. The Trabant was removed and replaced with a Tilt-A-Whirl, retaining the Circus Wheel name.\n|-\n|Circus Wheel\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1981\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2008\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Sellner Manufacturing]]\n|This Sellner [[Tilt-A-Whirl]] was known in the past under the names Fiesta Dance 1981-1981; Baile de las Flores 1982\u20131988 and Jolly Roger 1988\u20131999. The Tilt-A-Whirl was removed to make room for 3-Point Challenge basketball game, which was replaced by CraZanity. Tilt-A-Whirl has been in storage in a boneyard.\n|-\n|[[Twisted Colossus|Colossus]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1978\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2014\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[International Amusement Devices]]\n|The iconic wooden coaster, which had two tracks, was redesigned in August 2014 as Twisted Colossus, a converted hybrid coaster. \n|-\n|Condor\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1988\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1989\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Huss Rides]]\n|This Huss Condor was open for two years before being removed. It was removed to make room for Viper.\n|-\n|Crazy Barrels\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1989\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|This Intamin Drunken Barrels was formerly located at a county fair. The Barrels were removed when the ride closed in 1989 and the platform for where the ride used to be was demolished in late 2017.\n|-\n|[[Goliath (Boomerang)|D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2001\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2011\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Vekoma]]\n|Located in \"Cyclone Bay\". A Floorless coaches suspended beneath an overhead track traverse the track forward and in reverse. Removed and the coaster was sent to ''[[Six Flags New England]]'' as ''Goliath''.\n|-\n|Dragon\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1974\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1981\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow Development]]\n|This transportation [[cable railway]] transported riders from the upper level of the back of the mountain down to the lower level, and vice versa. The ride ceased operation in 1981 but was not removed until Ninja was built in 1988. Parts of the upper station were reused for Ninja, The Dragon's concrete track, wall, and lower station are visible to the left of Ninja's final lift hill.\n|-\n|Eagle's Flight \u2013 El Dorado\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1981\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|This Intamin aerial sky-way ride took passengers from the upper part of the mountain to the lower land on the north of the mountain. The station was next to El Bumpo's area.\n|-\n|Eagle's Flight \u2013 Galaxy\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1994\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|A second aerial sky-way ride from the top of the mountain to the lower land in the County Fair area.\n|-\n|El-Bumpo\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1979\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow Development]]\n|Gas-powered bumper boats located on the pond.\n|-Enterprise\n|[[Flashback (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Flashback]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1992\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2008\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|Steel roller coaster featuring a stacked design and numerous steep rolling track dives. The Flashback was standing but not operating starting in 2003 and demolished and scrapped in 2008.\n|-\n|Freefall\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1982\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2008\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|An Intamin 1st-generation Freefall. The ride was standing but not operating from 2005 to 2006; however, it was scrapped for the 2008 season.\n|-\n|{{Anchor|Galaxy}}Galaxy<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20140223114829/http://www.vintagedisneylandtickets.com/images/MM1971a.jpg</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1979\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|{{nowrap|Astron International Corporation}}\n|A Robinson double Ferris wheel with cable pulley that looked like a V-shaped beam. The ride was removed and was located where Buccaneer and Swashbuckler are now sitting. It was relocated to [[California's Great America]] and then later removed.\n|-\n|Grand Centennial Excursion Railroad\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1975\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1985\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|\n|A {{RailGauge|3ft|lk=on}} narrow gauge<ref>[https://pcrailroad.wordpress.com/2007/01/27/a-history-of-no-1/ Pacific Coast Railroad Company - A History of No. 1]</ref> steam train that took passengers around. Located north of the main mountain.\n|-\n|Granny Gran Prix\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2007\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Morgan Manufacturing|D. H. Morgan]]\n|This track-guided car ride was known as Chevron Gran Prix (Gas Powered) from 1971\u20131986. A new turnpike (electric-powered) was opened for three years before being moved in 1988 to Bugs Bunny World. The old guided track was demolished to make room for Tidal Wave. In December 2007 it was demolished to make room for Thomas Town's opening in 2008.\n|-\n\n|[[Green Lantern: First Flight (roller coaster)|Green Lantern: First Flight]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2011\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2017\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|A 4th Dimension roller coaster which was the first ZacSpin model in the United States and the second at the park following [[X2 (roller coaster)|X2]] from [[Arrow Dynamics]]. Removed in 2019 and the coaster will reopen at La Ronde as Vip\u00e8re in 2020 <ref>https://www.sixflags.com/larondeen/newfor2020</ref> \n|-\n|Jolly Monster\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1973\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1981\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|Eyerly\n|A standard Eyerly Monster ride which replaced Billy the Squid. This thrill ride was at the Pirate's Cove near Colossus, Buccaneer, and Swashbuckler. The ride was removed and its site sat empty for 7 years before the Tilt-A-Whirl was moved there.\n|-\n|Little Sailor Ride\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1985\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|\n|Yankee Doodle Dandy (1971\u20131972) Sailboat Ride (1973\u20131980) Little Sailor Ride (1981\u20131985)\n|-\n|[[Log Jammer (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Log Jammer]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2011\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow Development]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Log flume featuring two large drops. Removed to make way for Full Throttle.\n|-\n|Magic Pagoda\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1974\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1984\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|\n|A walk-thru attraction located on Samurai Summit. It featured a talking Buddha, a mirror maze, a strobe light room (with a dragon flying overhead), a walk through a miniature version of Chinatown and various other small scale items of interest with a Chinese Theme. Now used as part of a walk-through maze for the Halloween season.\n|-\n|Metro\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2011\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|Universal Mobility\n|This monorail ride ran three stations; one at the High Sierra Territory (Demolished, now serves as Reds Revenge Haunted Maze during Frightfest), one at the Colossus County Fair (Demolished in 2017 to make room for the CraZanity Pendulum ride) and one at Samurai Summit (this station is currently used as the launch tunnel for Full Throttle). The monorail had been standing but not operating since 2001 and it was announced by Six Flags in 2007 that the ride would have no plans to reopen. The trains were located near the former location of Flashback where they sat for 10 years. In 2011 the monorail trains are relocated to [[Hersheypark]]. The abandoned track has been taken down in all areas readily visible to parkgoers but sections of track still exist and may be glimpsed in heavily overgrown sections of the park such as the area behind Buccaneer and Swashbuckler.\n|-\n|Mountain Express\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1973\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1982\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Anton Schwarzkopf]]\n|Wildcat coaster located near where Flashback stood. Relocated to Magic Landing as Wildcat and then to Bosque Magico as Montana Rusa.\n|-\n|[[Psyclone (roller coaster)|Psyclone]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1991\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2006\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Dinn Corporation]]\n|A wood tracked roller coaster patterned after the Cyclone at Astroland park in Brooklyn, New York. It was torn down for the 2007 season, and piles of wood remained at the site for many days after the destruction. The site is now home to another wooden coaster, Apocalypse.\n|-\n|Reactor\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1977\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1993\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Anton Schwarzkopf]]\n|A Schwarzkopf Enterprise, known from 1977\u20131987 as Enterprise, was renamed Reactor in 1987. This thrill ride was removed at the end of the 1993 season.\n|-\n|[[La Vibora|Sarajevo Bobsleds]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1984\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1986\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|Bobsled coaster named after the 1984 Olympics. Removed due to the Six Flags ride rotation program and replaced with Shockwave. It was moved to Six Flags Over Texas and opened as Avalanche, but was later renamed and rethemed as La Vibora to better match the Spain section of the park.\n|-\n|Scrambler\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1973\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2003\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Eli Bridge]]\n|This scrambler had a lot of damage from an uprooted tree and was scrapped; however, Six Flags Magic Mountain received another scrambler from Six Flags Over Texas.\n|-\n|[[Batman The Escape|Shockwave ]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1986\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1988\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|A Steel Standup looping roller coaster. it was removed in 1989 and relocated to Six Flags Great Adventure due to the ride rotation program.\n|-\n|Sierra Twist\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1973\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2008\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Anton Schwarzkopf]]\n|A Schwarzkopf [[Bayern Kurve]] ride, originally known as Swiss Twist. It was a high-speed bobsled ride with a circular track. The ride was removed due to aging parts and high maintenance costs.\n|-\n|Spin Out\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2008\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Chance Rides]]\n|A [[Rotor (ride)|Chance Rotor]] known from 1971\u20131972 as Bottoms Up. Featured in the video for [[Belinda Carlisle]]'s No. 1 hit song, \"Heaven is a Place on Earth\" \n|-\n|Thrill Shot\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2001\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2012\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[S&S Worldwide]]\n|Rapidly ascending slingshot attraction. The ride requires a nominal fee from guests to participate. Thrill Shot closed in 2009 and never reopened due to high maintenance costs. In early 2012, Thrill Shot was removed.\n|-\n|Tumble Drum\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1974\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1980\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|\n|This walk-through barrel roll was located near the Electric Rainbow (Round up ride).\n|-\n|Yosemite Sam Sierra Falls\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1993\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2010\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|WhiteWater West Industries\n|Double tube waterslides with dingy raft on location at the Bugs Bunny World. Demolished to make room for Road Runner Express.\n|-\n|Z-Force\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1987\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1993\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|An Intamin Looping Starship/Space Shuttle themed as an Air Force fighter plane. The ride was removed at the end of the season in 1993 to make room for [[Batman: The Ride]].\n|}\n\n==Rankings==\n[[File:SFMM- Riddlers Revenge.JPG|thumb|The Riddler's Revenge, the world's tallest and fastest stand-up roller coaster featuring six inversions.]]\n[[File:SFMM- Full Throttle 1.JPG|thumb|Full Throttle is a launch roller coaster which features the world's second highest vertical loop at {{convert|160|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}.]]\nSix Flags Magic Mountain's coasters are commonly ranked high in Amusement Today's annual [[Golden Ticket Awards]]. With the opening of Full Throttle on June 22, 2013, Six Flags Magic Mountain obtained the world record for the largest number of roller coasters in an amusement park.\n\nBelow is a table with roller coasters at Six Flags Magic Mountain and their highest ranking in the Golden Ticket Awards.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.goldenticketawards.com/pdfs/at_goldenticket_2012_web.pdf|title=Amusement Today&nbsp;\u2014 Golden Ticket Winners 2012|format=PDF|magazine=Amusement Today|accessdate=September 10, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120919232328/http://www.goldenticketawards.com/pdfs/at_goldenticket_2012_web.pdf|archivedate=September 19, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Roller Coaster\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Highest Rank\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[X\u00b2 (roller coaster)|X\u00b2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Tatsu]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|28\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Goliath (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Goliath]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Twisted Colossus]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Full Throttle (roller coaster)|Full Throttle]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|39\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[The Riddler's Revenge]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|39\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Batman: The Ride]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Apocalypse: The Ride]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|27\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Scream (roller coaster)|Scream]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|52\n|-\n|}\n\n===Record breaking rides===\nSix Flags Magic Mountain has several attractions that set world records in various categories.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Ride\n!align=\"left\"|Type of ride\n!align=\"left\"|Opening Date\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Record(s)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Height\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[The New Revolution (roller coaster)|The New Revolution]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Steel roller coaster]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|May 8, 1976\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |First [[vertical loop]]ing roller coaster built since 1901.<ref name=\"Coney Island History\">{{cite web|last=Sandy|first=Adam|title=Coney Island History|url=http://www.ultimaterollercoaster.com/coasters/history/early_1900/coney_island.shtml|work=Roller Coaster History|publisher=Ultimate Roller Coaster|accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref>  World's tallest roller coaster when it opened to the public.<ref name=\"Revolution34\">{{cite news|last=William-Ross|first=Lindsay|title=You Say You Want a Revolution? Magic Mountain's Turns 34 Today|url=http://laist.com/2010/05/08/you_say_you_want_a_revolution_magic.php|accessdate=3 July 2013|newspaper=LAist|date=8 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618221208/http://laist.com/2010/05/08/you_say_you_want_a_revolution_magic.php|archivedate=June 18, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|113|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Superman: Escape from Krypton]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Shuttle roller coaster]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Superman: The Escape: March 15, 1997\nSuperman: Escape from Krypton; March 19, 2011\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|One of the world's first 2 roller coasters to reach 100&nbsp;mph.\nFirst roller coaster to reach {{convert|400|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}. becoming the world's tallest coaster until 2003.\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|415|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[The Riddler's Revenge]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Stand-up roller coaster]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|April 4, 1998\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|World's tallest, longest & fastest stand-up roller coaster.\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|156|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Goliath (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Goliath]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Steel roller coaster\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|February 11, 2000\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|World's longest & fastest initial drop ({{convert|255|ft|m|0|abbr=on|disp=or}}) on a closed-circuit coaster until May 13, 2000.\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|235|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[X\u00b2 (roller coaster)|X\u00b2]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[4th Dimension roller coaster]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|X: January 12, 2002 ; X\u00b2: May 24, 2008\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |World's first [[4th dimension roller coaster]].\nFeatures flipping seats, chainlift music, fog and fire.\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|175|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Tatsu]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Flying roller coaster]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|May 13, 2006\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|World's tallest, fastest & longest flying coaster. Features world's biggest pretzel loop.\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|170|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Lex Luthor: Drop of Doom]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Drop tower]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|July 7, 2012\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|World's tallest tower drop ride when it opened in 2012. Its record was broken by [[Zumanjaro: Drop of Doom]] in 2014.\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|400|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Full Throttle (roller coaster)|Full Throttle]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Launched roller coaster]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|June 22, 2013\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|First launched roller coaster featuring \"top hat\" constructed on a vertical loop. World's highest vertical loop when built.\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|160|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|CraZanity\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Pendulum ride]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|July 13, 2018\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|World's Tallest Pendulum Ride\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|172|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Greater Los Angeles}}\n\n* [[Incidents at Six Flags parks]]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage|Magic Mountain}}\n* {{official website|http://www.sixflags.com/magicMountain/}}\n* {{RCDB|4532}}\n{{Six Flags}}\n{{Six Flags Magic Mountain}}\n{{Amusement Parks & Theme Parks of California}}\n{{Santa Clara River}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Six Flags Magic Mountain}}\n[[Category:Six Flags Magic Mountain| ]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks in California]]\n[[Category:Santa Clarita, California]]\n[[Category:Six Flags amusement parks|Magic Mountain]]\n[[Category:1971 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks opened in 1971]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{short description|Theme park in Valencia, California}}\n{{Infobox amusement park\n| name = Six Flags Magic Mountain\n| logo = Six Flags Magic Mountain logo.png\n| image = File:Six Flags Magic Mountain (13208988393).jpg\n| caption = The entrance archway to the park in 2014.\n| location = [[Valencia, Santa Clarita, California|Valencia]]\n| location2 = [[Santa Clarita, California|Santa Clarita]]\n| location3 = [[California]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|34.427|-118.597|display=title,inline|region:US-CA_type:landmark_source:dewiki}}\n| homepage = [http://www.sixflags.com/magicmountain Six Flags Magic Mountain]\n| owner = [[Six Flags]]\n| opening_date = {{Start date and age|1971|05|29}}\n| previous_names = ''Magic Mountain'' <span style=\"white-space: nowrap\">- 1971 to 1979</span>\n| season = Year round\n| visitors = 3.365 million in 2017<ref name=\"2017 attendance\">{{cite web|title=TEA/AECOM 2017 Global Attractions Attendance Report Report|url=http://www.teaconnect.org/images/files/TEA_268_653730_180517.pdf|publisher=[[Themed Entertainment Association]] |accessdate=May 21, 2018|date=May 21, 2018}}</ref>\n| area = {{convert|262|acre|ha|abbr=on}}\n| coasters = 19\n| water_rides = 3\n| slogan = \u201cThrill Capital of the World\u201d\n| status = Operating\n}}\n \n'''Six Flags Magic Mountain''', originally '''Magic Mountain''', is a {{convert|262|acre|ha|adj=on}} [[theme park]] located in the [[Valencia, Santa Clarita, California|Valencia]] neighborhood of [[Santa Clarita, California|Santa Clarita]], [[California]], {{convert|35|mi|km}} northwest of [[downtown Los Angeles]]. It opened on May 29, 1971, as a development of the [[Newhall Land and Farming Company]].<ref name=\"ech\">{{cite encyclopedia | title=The Newhall Land and Farming Company | encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Company Histories | publisher=The Gale Group | url=http://www.answers.com/topic/the-newhall-land-and-farming-company | accessdate=April 20, 2007}}</ref> In 1979, [[Six Flags]] purchased the park and added the name \"Six Flags\" to the park's name.\n\nWith 19 roller coasters, Six Flags Magic Mountain holds the world record for most roller coasters in an amusement park.<ref name=\"Six Flags Magic Mountain to reclaim roller coaster title\">{{cite news|last=MacDonald|first=Brady|title=Six Flags Magic Mountain to reclaim roller coaster title|url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/deals/themeparks/la-trb-six-flags-magic-mountain-cedar-point-coaster-capital-05201202,0,745879.story|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=May 2, 2012|date=May 2, 2012}}</ref> In 2017, the park had an estimated 3.3 million visitors, ranking it sixteenth in attendance in North America.<ref name=\"2017 attendance\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:SixFlagsmagicMountain.JPG|thumb|Six Flags Magic Mountain from [[Interstate 5]]]]\n[[File:SFMM- Grand Carousel 2.JPG|thumb|right|Grand Carousel is a family friendly ride located in the Six Flags Plaza area.]]\n[[File:SFMM- Jet Stream 1.JPG|thumb|right|[[Jet Stream (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Jet Stream]] is a family friendly flume ride located near the entrance to Gold Rusher. The ride opened in 1972.]]\nWhen the park opened, there were 500 employees and 33 attractions, many of which were designed and built by [[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow Development Co.]] which designed and built many of the original attractions at Disneyland. The admission price in 1971 was $5 for adults, and $3.50 for children between the ages of 3 and 12. Because the park was in a relatively remote part of Los Angeles County, the [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound bus line]] provided bus service to and from the park and Los Angeles, as well as from Northern California, and optionally allowed purchase of park admission at the time the bus ticket was purchased.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.paul-robinson.us/index.php/2012/01/09/rtd?blog=6 | title = Remembering RTD and the \"good old days\" of cheap LA area public transit | date = January 9, 2012 | first = Paul | last = Robinson | work = Stories, Parables, and Long Items | access-date = February 4, 2013 | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141129075956/http://www.paul-robinson.us/index.php/2012/01/09/rtd?blog=6 | archive-date = November 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt its 1971 opening, the rides and attractions included [[Gold Rusher]], a steel coaster; the [[Log Jammer (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Log Jammer]], a log flume; the Sky Tower, an [[observation tower]]; Grand Prix, similar to Disneyland's Autopia ride; El Bumpo, bumper boats; a [[Carousel]]; and other smaller rides. There were four transportation rides to the peak: Funicular, a [[cable railway]] or [[funicular]], later renamed '''Orient Express'''; the Metro, which consist three monorail stations around the park: Whitewater Lake, Country Fair, and Mountain stations; and \"Eagles Flight\", a skyride that combined two stations at the peak: the long one north to Galaxy Station, and the short one west to El Dorado Station.  The Showcase Theater (renamed Golden Bear Theater), was part of the original park and featured [[Barbra Streisand]] as the first of many headline performers who would appear at Magic Mountain over the years.\n\nIn the 1971 season, Magic Mountain obtained permission from [[Warner Bros.]] to use [[Looney Tunes]] characters. However, they did not continue using the characters after their first year. In 1972, they began using trolls as the park mascots. The trolls King Blop, also known as King Troll, Bleep, Bloop, and the Wizard became recognizable symbols of Magic Mountain. All King Productions, a contractor, provided the entertainers wearing the costumes until December 31, 1972, when Magic Mountain took on that role. The characters were used until 1985. Also in 1972, a second flume ride named [[Jet Stream (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Jet Stream]] was added.\n\nIn 1973 the park added its second roller coaster, the Mountain Express, a compact [[Anton Schwarzkopf|Schwarzkopf]] Wildcat model steel coaster.  In 1974 the park also installed a new complex of spinning rides in what would later be known as Back Street. The new additions consisted of the Himalaya, Electric Rainbow, and Tumble Drum. In 1975, the Grand Centennial Railway opened in the Back Street. It took riders on a train journey to Spillikin Corners and back.\n\n===The Coaster Revolution===\n[[File:SFMM- Roaring Rapids 2.JPG|thumb|Roaring Rapids is a river rafting water ride at Six Flags Magic Mountain.]]\nWith the opening of [[The New Revolution (roller coaster)|Great American Revolution]] in 1976, Magic Mountain became the first park in the world to have a modern, 360-degree steel looping coaster (though previous roller coasters with loops had been built and dismantled elsewhere due to safety issues). When it was built, there was very little in the way of surrounding brush. Now, the tracks are surrounded by trees and bushes, which prevents the riders from knowing the track layout beforehand. [[Universal Pictures|Universal]] then filmed a major movie at Magic Mountain with the Revolution as its centerpiece called [[Rollercoaster (1977 film)|''Rollercoaster'']] in 1977. \n[[File:SFMM- Colossus 2.JPG|thumb|Colossus was a wooden roller coaster which opened in 1978.]]\nIn 1978, [[Colossus (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Colossus]], at the time the fastest, largest dual-tracked wooden coaster, opened. Following its first season, it was closed and extensively redone. When it reopened, it was a much smoother ride. In 1991, the camel hump before the last, or third, turn was replaced by a block brake. Though it decreased the speed of the ride after this particular brake, it did allow three trains to run per side at a time, greatly increasing capacity. One of the trains sometimes ran backwards for a few years in the mid-80s. However, until the late 1990s this kind of ride was no longer possible due to the newer ride system in place, as well as different trains. During ''Fright Fest'', the park runs one side backwards using a set of trains acquired from the now demolished [[Psyclone (roller coaster)|Psyclone]] which was located on the other side of the park. In 2015, the coaster was re-tracked with steel tracking and several inversions were added to the coaster. It was subsequently rebranded \"[[Twisted Colossus]]\". This renovation was completed by [[Rocky Mountain Construction]].\n\n===Six Flags era===\n[[File:Goliath drop.JPG|thumb|left|The opening drop on [[Goliath (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Goliath]]. Goliath featured the longest drop on a closed circuit roller coaster when it opened in February 2000.]]\nIn 1979, the park was sold to Six Flags and became known as Six Flags Magic Mountain. In 1981, Six Flags Magic Mountain introduced a ride that was on the west coast for the first time called [[Roaring Rapids]]. It was developed by [[Intamin]] in conjunction with the now defunct [[Six Flags Astroworld]], which had opened a similar ride in 1979. Along with Rapids came the completion of the midway near Spillikin Corners to link with Revolution's area. Finally, a complete circuit could be made around the park. It was originally designed as a dual-sided station, but only one was fully developed, and all that exists of the possible second side is a few supports. It uses large pumps to circulate water, and each of the two pumps can circulate 88,500 gallons per minute. The reservoir can hold 1.5 million gallons of water, and one of the innovations used on it was the introduction of guide boards to help eliminate jam ups.\n\nIn 1982, the attraction [[Freefall (ride)|Freefall]] was added. Also built by [[Intamin]], it was considered a cutting edge drop tower ride, if not strictly a \"roller coaster.\" It simply ascends the tower and then drops down, with the track curving to horizontal, leaving riders on their backs. Others were built for other parks (some of which are Six Flags). Today, most of these rides are obsolete and have been removed. Some flat rides were added and others removed the next year.\n\nIn 1984, [[Sarajevo Bobsleds]] was erected. Yet another ride built by [[Intamin]], the coaster was basically a bobsled without ice and snow. The coaster was built in honor of the [[1984 Winter Olympics|1984 Olympics]]. [[Six Flags Great Adventure]] added a similar ride that same year. In 1986, [[Sarajevo Bobsleds]] was removed and now operates at [[Six Flags Over Texas]] as [[La Vibora]]. The other bobsled was moved to [[Six Flags Great America]] and later to [[The Great Escape & Splashwater Kingdom|The Great Escape]] in [[Queensbury, New York]], where it operates as [[Alpine Bobsled]].\n\nIn 1985, Children's World was rethemed as [[Bugs Bunny]] World, as Magic Mountain had abandoned the Trolls in favor of the Warner Brothers' characters. That year, [[Michael Jackson]] visited the park, riding rides such as Colossus, Revolution and Roaring Rapids. In 1986, the park added a steel stand-up looping roller coaster called [[Batman The Escape|Shockwave]] designed by Intamin. This coaster was located in the back of the park replacing Sarajevo Bobsleds. At the end of 1988, the coaster was removed as part of a ride rotation program and went to Six Flags Great Adventure in 1990. It was removed from there in 1992 and was repainted white and rethemed upon its removal to [[Six Flags Astroworld]]. There it was known as Batman The Escape. When Astroworld closed in 2005, the ride was put in storage at [[Darien Lake]].\n\nIn 1987, the park re-themed the Back Street. Spinning flat rides were renamed Turbo (Electric Rainbow), Subway (Himalaya), and Reactor (Enterprise). The dance club was rethemed as well, and located near Reactor. After Hours, as it was now called (formerly Decibels), for one summer stayed open later than the rest of the park. It, along with Back Street, would stay open an additional two hours as a place for locals to hang out. This format lasted one season.\n\nIn 1988 [[Ninja (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Ninja]], \"The Black Belt of Roller Coasters\", opened. Built by [[Arrow Dynamics]], it was the first [[suspended swing roller coaster]] on the West coast. Ninja has gone through very few changes since it was opened in 1988; evidently only the wheels and paint have been changed.\n[[File:SFMM- Tidal Wave 1.JPG|thumb|[[Tidal Wave (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Tidal Wave]] is a Shoot the Chute water ride, featuring a {{Convert|50|ft|adj=on}} splashdown into a large body of water.]]\n[[Tidal Wave (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Tidal Wave]] opened in 1989. It is a short, wet ride featuring a large boat that travels up a low-angled incline to a level water trough. The trough, in the shape of a semicircle, ends in a steep drop into a large splashpool. The impact displaces large amounts of water on its riders. The ride's exit ramp crosses over the splashpool, allowing willing patrons leaving the ride to get soaked from the splash.\n\n[[File:Six Flags Magic Mountain Viper and X2 from Sky Tower cropped version.jpg|thumb|left|Viper, seen in the foreground, was constructed in the park in 1990]]\n\nIn 1990, [[Viper (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Viper]], a multiple looping coaster designed by [[Arrow Dynamics]] opened. It features a {{convert|188|ft|m|adj=on}} drop, speeds up to {{convert|70|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}, 3 [[Inclined loop|vertical loops]], a batwing turn that inverts riders twice, and a double corkscrew.\n\nIn 1991, Magic Mountain added [[Psyclone (roller coaster)|Psyclone]], modeled after the [[Coney Island Cyclone]]. The Spillikin Corners area of the park was re-themed as Cyclone Bay to suit the new coaster, drawing guests into this area. The change was largely cosmetic, as the earlier theme relied on retail establishments that had been removed previously. The Glass Blower had been replaced by the Shooting Gallery, and the Candy Kitchen viewing area was redesigned. With Psyclone, the crowds returned. Due to the 1994 Northridge earthquake, Psyclone's structure was damaged, and the ride was eventually removed in 2007. After adding Ninja, Viper, and Psyclone within 4 years, the park was getting a large repertoire of big roller coasters.\n\nThe next year, 1992, a coaster built by Intamin called [[Flashback (roller coaster)|Flashback]] was added. This one-of-a-kind ride, originally planned to be enclosed in a building, had already operated at [[Six Flags Great America]] and [[Six Flags Over Georgia]] prior to its arrival. Very steep, short drops were designed to make riders feel like they were \"diving\" down in a plane, and it ended in a 540 degree upward spiral. But, because of the shoulder harnesses, riders were subjected to a lot of head banging. This coaster rarely ran by 1996 (it created too much noise for the nearby water park) and on January 23, 2007, the park announced that Flashback would be removed along with Psyclone. The park also stated that Flashback might be re-built elsewhere within the park for 2008 but the ride was finally scrapped at the end of 2008.\n\n===Time Warner era===\nIn 1993 Six Flags Magic Mountain entered the Time Warner era.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-09-21/business/fi-37629_1_time-warner |title=Time Warner Completes Six Flags Purchase \u2013 Los Angeles Times |newspaper=Los Angeles Times }}</ref> The new ride for the year was Yosemite Sam Sierra Falls. It was a water ride that has two twisting tubes that riders could slide down in using a raft. Also that year, there was re-theming and High Sierra Territory was opened. The Showcase Theatre became Golden Bear Theater, the Animal Star Theatre was created in Bugs Bunny World, and a large, fake, wooden tree was built. This year also saw the end of live non-Christian themed concerts in the park due to the riot that broke out as a result of a \"TLC\" concert that was oversold. Magic Mountain was quickly overwhelmed by large crowds that vandalized and destroyed property.  Park shops had their windows broken and looting quickly followed. Police were called to the scene in full riot gear. The park was evacuated and closed down for the night.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-04-19/local/me-24654_1_magic-mountain |title=Magic Mountain Reopens After Melees \u2013 Los Angeles Times |newspaper=Los Angeles Times }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Magic Mountain added what two other Six Flags parks already had, a [[Bolliger & Mabillard]] inverted looping roller coaster called [[Batman: The Ride]] (which other Six Flags parks also added in the coming years). Batman: the Ride (BTR) is an inverted coaster, meaning the usual coaster protocol is reversed; the track is overhead and the cars are below it. The trains travel on the outside of the loops, and rider's legs hang freely, as on a ski lift.\n\n[[File:SFMM- Sign 2.JPG|thumb|Signs to nearby rides and other attractions]]\nIn 1995, a separately gated waterpark called [[Six Flags Hurricane Harbor]] opened in June. The park included body slides, tube slides, a kiddie water play area, lazy river, and a wave pool. The following year, a [[SkyCoaster]] called Dive Devil opened at Magic Mountain.\n\nA dual launch coaster called [[Superman: Escape From Krypton|Superman: The Escape]] debuted at the park on March 15, 1997. Designed by [[Intamin]], the 30-second ride launches riders from 0 to {{Convert|100|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} in seven seconds on a track that scales up a 41-story tower. It was the first roller coaster in the world to reach speeds of 100&nbsp;mph. In 2011, it received a new color scheme and was renamed \"Superman: Escape From Krypton\". In addition, the trains were reversed to provide a backward-facing launch.\n\n[[File:SFMM- Riddler's Revenge 5.JPG|thumb|The [[The Riddler's Revenge|Riddler's Revenge]] is a [[stand-up roller coaster]] which features 6 inversions.]]\nIn 1998, a new Bolliger & Mabillard [[Stand-up roller coaster]] called [[Riddler's Revenge]] opened as the tallest and fastest stand-up roller coaster in the world.\n\n===Premier Parks era===\nAlso in 1998 Six Flags was sold to Premier Parks. The next year saw no dramatic changes. In 2000, a steel [[hypercoaster]], [[Goliath (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Goliath]], was added. It was built by [[Giovanola]].\n\n2001 was to be the year of three new roller coasters, but only one actually opened on time: [[Goliath Jr.]], a steel kiddie coaster. The other two, [[Giant Inverted Boomerang|D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu]] and [[X\u00b2 (roller coaster)|X]] (now X\u00b2), had mechanical problems. D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu opened late in 2001 and X opened early in 2002. D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu was designed by [[Vekoma]] and is a Giant Inverted Boomerang coaster (GIB), a variant of their popular [[Boomerang (roller coaster)|Boomerang]] design. It is an inverted coaster with coaches suspended beneath an overhead track that traverses an open-circuit track forward and in reverse and features two completely vertical drops and three inversions. It opened late in 2001, but suffered a lot of downtime. X was designed by Arrow Dynamics, as the world's first \"fourth-dimensional\" roller coaster. It is the only one in North America where riders experience going 360 degrees in their seats. Each seat lies on a separate axis from the track. This coaster managed to open briefly on January 7, 2002, only to close due to more technical problems. It reopened late in August of that year. The ride closed for a major refurbishment and re-theme in 2008 where X transformed into X\u00b2.\n\nIn 2003, [[Scream (roller coaster)|Scream]], designed by Bolliger & Mabillard was added. At this point, Six Flags Magic Mountain tied with [[Cedar Point]] for the park with the most roller coasters in the United States. Scream is similar in concept with [[Medusa (Six Flags Discovery Kingdom)|Medusa]] at [[Six Flags Discovery Kingdom]] and is a mirror image of [[Bizarro (Six Flags Great Adventure)|Bizarro]] at [[Six Flags Great Adventure]]. It is a [[floorless roller coaster]] with trains riding above the rails traversing seven inversions on {{convert|3985|ft|m}} of track on floorless trains. In 2006, [[Tatsu]], a Bolliger & Mabillard [[flying roller coaster]] was added, causing a temporary closure of Revolution to allow construction to take place. It was much larger than the other three Bolliger & Mabillard Flying Coasters at other Six Flags parks, all named [[Superman: Ultimate Flight]].  Tatsu has a suspended-track orientation featuring vehicles that recline passengers with their backs against the track and facing the ground. This brought the park up to 17 roller coasters, to tie with Cedar Point for the greatest number of roller coasters in a park (albeit Flashback had been standing but not operating for an extended period of time and thus it is debatable whether the park could claim 17 as its number of roller coasters).\n\n===2006 attempted sale===\nOn June 22, 2006, Six Flags, Inc. announced that it was exploring options for six of its parks, including Magic Mountain and its neighboring water park, [[Six Flags Hurricane Harbor|Hurricane Harbor]]. Though management said closing the park was unlikely, rumors still began that the park could be sold to real estate developers, with an intent to close the park and build housing developments in the area.<ref>{{cite press release | publisher=Business Wire |date=June 22, 2006 | title=Six Flags to Explore Strategic Options for Six Properties \u2013 Buffalo, Concord, Denver, Seattle, Houston and Los Angeles; Company Provides Mid-Quarter Update on Operations | url=http://investors.sixflags.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=61629&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=875468&highlight= | accessdate=June 27, 2006}}</ref> Park officials cited dwindling attendance due to rowdy behavior among some of the park-goers (notably gang members and other teenagers and young adults, who account for a large percentage of the park's attendance{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=January 2016}}) as reasons for wanting to sell the park while management was wanting to move Six Flags into more of a family park direction.<ref>{{cite web|first=Lance |last=Hart |url=http://www.screamscape.com/html/six_flags_magic_mountain.htm |title=Six Flags Magic Mountain |publisher=Screamscape.com |date=May 4, 2007 }}</ref> Throughout the Six Flags chain, attendance in the second quarter of 2006 was 14 percent lower than it was in the second quarter of 2005.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.the-signal.com/?module=displaystory&story_id=31912&format=html | url-status = dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070224164921/http://www.the-signal.com/?module=displaystory&story_id=31912&format=html | archive-date=February 24, 2007 | title = Six Flags Posts 2Q Loss of $39.6 Mil. | first = Adam | last = Clark | date = August 3, 2006 | work = [[The Santa Clarita Valley Signal]]}}</ref>\n\nBy the fall of 2006, Six Flags announced that Magic Mountain was still up for sale. They also stated, however, that it would be sold to a company that would continue to operate it as a park, and that closing Magic Mountain was not a possibility. [[Cedar Fair]], [[Anheuser-Busch]], and several others considered buying the park but none of the offers came close to the asking price.\n\nWhen Six Flags announced which parks it was selling in January 2007, Magic Mountain was no longer one of them. The company decided not to sell Magic Mountain and its adjacent water park. Spokeswoman Wendy Goldberg said that upon further evaluation, the company decided that the Los Angeles parks remained too valuable to relinquish, as sales were increasing, and that the park would not be sold. Other parks were sold as a package and remained open.\n\n===2007\u2013present===\n[[File:SFMM Magic Flyer.jpg|thumb|Magic flyer roller coaster]]\n[[File:SFMM- Scream.jpg|thumb|Scream roller coaster]]\n[[File:Tatsu.jpg|thumb|right|[[Tatsu]], one of the roller coasters at Six Flags Magic Mountain.]]\n[[File:SFMM- Twisted Colossus 2.jpg|thumb|[[Twisted Colossus]], one of Magic Mountain's most signature and iconic roller coasters. Colossus was shut down in 2014 to become reborn as Twisted Colossus. ]]\n\nPsyclone was removed in 2007, and Flashback was demolished in early 2008. As a result, Six Flags Magic Mountain no longer tied the record for the most roller coasters in a single park, relinquishing the record to [[Cedar Point]] \u2013 the park's total had never surpassed Cedar Point but had tied numerous times. The park began focusing more attention on marketing with family-oriented values, and a new children's theme area, [[Thomas the Tank Engine and Friends|Thomas Town]], was added in 2008. The park renovated one its thrill rides, however. \"X\" was closed in late 2007 for its transformation into X<sup>2</sup> which featured new fourth-generation trains, a new paint job, and special effects that included flame throwers and audio. It reopened in 2008. In the same year, the park began work on the \"Magic of the Mountain\" museum at the top of its Sky Tower attraction that contained memorabilia throughout the park's history including old television commercials, park maps, models, and equipment saved from defunct rides.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/news/ci_8412730 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080304113622/http://www.dailynews.com/news/ci_8412730 |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 4, 2008 |title=Teen creating some magic with his Six Flags museum \u2013 LA Daily News |newspaper=Daily News |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Apocalypse: The Ride|Terminator Salvation: The Ride]], a wooden roller coaster, opened on May 23, 2009. It was built in the former location of [[Psyclone (roller coaster)|Psyclone]] and featured tunnels, spraying mist, and special effects. On January 9, 2011, the ride was renamed to Apocalypse and given an appropriate theme that reflects an \"end of the world\" scenario.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimaterollercoaster.com/news/stories/20081022_01.shtml |title=Six Flags Announces Terminator Coaster For Magic Mountain |publisher=Ultimate Rollercoaster |date=October 22, 2008}}</ref> Later that year, Six Flags President and CEO Mark Shapiro said in a [[Los Angeles Times]] published interview that Magic Mountain had plans to install a new roller coaster for its 2010 season, and would add a new themed area for children in 2011 called [[Wiggles World]]. Shapiro also stated that the adjacent Hurricane Harbor would receive an expansion.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://travel.latimes.com/daily-deal-blog/index.php/magic-mountain-highl-4258/#more-4258 | newspaper=LA Times | title=Magic Mountain \u2018highly profitable' despite bankruptcy cloud looming over Six Flags|date=March 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn May 29, 2010, [[Road Runner Express (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Mr. Six's Dance Coaster]] was scheduled to open but it was delayed until 2011 when it would open under a new theme.<ref>{{cite news|last=MacDonald|first=Brady|title=Six Flags Magic Mountain delays launch of 17th coaster until 2011|url=http://travel.latimes.com/daily-deal-blog/index.php/six-flags-magic-moun-6992/|accessdate=October 16, 2010|newspaper=LA Times|date=May 27, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"2011 plans as at August 2010\">{{cite news|last=MacDonald|first=Brady|title=Superman coaster at Six Flags Magic Mountain to get major makeover in 2011|url=http://travel.latimes.com/daily-deal-blog/index.php/superman-magic-mount-7321/|accessdate=October 16, 2010|newspaper=LA Times|date=August 3, 2010}}</ref> On the same day, Mr. Six's Splash Island opened at the adjacent Hurricane Harbor water park.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr. Six's Splash Island to Debut Memorial Day Weekend|url=http://www.sixflags.com/hurricaneHarborLA/info/News_MrSixSplashIsland.aspx|publisher=Six Flags|accessdate=October 16, 2010|date=March 24, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231223418/http://www.sixflags.com/hurricaneHarborLA/info/News_MrSixSplashIsland.aspx|archivedate=December 31, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn August 3, 2010, it was announced that Superman: The Escape would undergo a major redevelopment before the 2011 season.<ref name=\"2011 plans as at August 2010\"/>\n\nOn October 20, 2010, Six Flags Magic Mountain officially announced their full plans for 2011 after a video was leaked six days earlier.<ref name=\"Screamscape\">{{cite web|last=Hart|first=Lance|title=Six Flags Magic Mountain|url=http://www.screamscape.com/html/six_flags_magic_mountain.htm|publisher=Screamscape|accessdate=October 21, 2010|date=October 14, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Official announcement\">{{cite web|last=Scollins|first=Mike|title=Magic Mountain: More Coasters Than Any Other Theme Park ON THE PLANET!|url=http://blog.sixflags.com/2010/10/magic-mountain-more-coasters-than-any-other-theme-park-on-the-planet/|publisher=Six Flags Blog|accessdate=October 21, 2010|date=October 20, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716080032/http://blog.sixflags.com/2010/10/magic-mountain-more-coasters-than-any-other-theme-park-on-the-planet/|archivedate=July 16, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In addition to opening Mr. Six's Dance Coaster under a new name and theme, Six Flags announced two other attractions. In time for the 2011 season, Superman: The Escape was refurbished to [[Superman: Escape from Krypton]] and featured new backwards launching cars and a new color scheme.<ref>{{cite news|title=Magic Mountain reveals new Green Lantern ride|url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news/entertainment&id=7735914|accessdate=October 21, 2010|newspaper=ABC|date=October 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=MacDonald|first=Brady|title=Six Flags Magic Mountain to run Superman coaster backward|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/oct/19/news/la-trb-superman-six-flags-magic-mountain-20101019|accessdate=October 21, 2010|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=October 19, 2010}}</ref> The third and final announcement regards an entirely new thrill roller coaster. The [[Green Lantern: First Flight (roller coaster)|Green Lantern: First Flight]] opened on July 1, 2011 as Magic Mountain's eighteenth roller coaster which was a [[Intamin]] [[4th dimension roller coaster|ZacSpin]]. This roller coaster reclaimed the world record for the highest number of roller coasters at a single theme park.<ref>{{cite news|last=MacDonald|first=Brady|title=Six Flags Magic Mountain aims to reclaim coaster crown with Green Lantern in 2011|url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/destinations/southerncalifornia/la-trb-green-lantern-magic-mountain-20111019,0,4055452.story|accessdate=October 21, 2010|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=October 19, 2010}}</ref> It was later announced, on November 4, 2010, that the children's roller coaster would be called [[Road Runner Express (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Road Runner Express]] and located in ''Bugs Bunny World''.<ref name=\"Six Flags Entertainment Corporation Investor Meeting\">{{cite web|title=Six Flags Entertainment Corporation Investor Meeting|url=http://investors.sixflags.com/phoenix.zhtml?p=irol-eventDetails&c=61629&eventID=3442475|work=WebCast|publisher=Six Flags|date=November 4, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105203813/http://investors.sixflags.com/phoenix.zhtml?p=irol-eventDetails&c=61629&eventID=3442475|archivedate=November 5, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Family Rides|url=http://www.sixflags.com/magicMountain/rides/FamilyRides.aspx|publisher=Six Flags Magic Mountain|author=Six Flags Magic Mountain}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2010, Six Flags began the process of removing non-[[Warner Bros.]] licensed theming from attractions. They terminated several licenses including [[Terminator (franchise)|Terminator]] and [[Thomas the Tank Engine]]. [[Apocalypse: The Ride|Terminator Salvation: The Ride]] was renamed and rethemed into ''Apocalypse'' which re-opened on January 8, 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=MacDonald|first=Brady|title=Six Flags Magic Mountain renaming Terminator wooden coaster|url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/deals/themeparks/la-trb-terminator-apocalypse-magic-mountain-20101203,1,1983895.story|accessdate=December 3, 2010|newspaper=LA Times|date=December 3, 2010}}</ref> Thomas Town was renamed and rethemed to [[Whistlestop Park]] in time for the 2011 season.<ref>{{cite news|last=MacDonald|first=Brady|title=Six Flags amusement parks prepare for thematic makeovers|url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/deals/themeparks/la-trb-six-flags-retheme-20101122,0,3267615.story|accessdate=November 27, 2010|newspaper=LA Times|date=November 25, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn January 18, 2011, the [[Los Angeles Times]] reported after considering a new theme based on [[DC Comics]] superhero sidekicks, the park opted for simplicity and renamed the Little Flash coaster to Road Runner Express.<ref name=\"LATimes update\">{{cite web|last=MacDonald|first=Brady|title=Five 'new' coasters coming to Six Flags Magic Mountain? Not so fast|url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/deals/themeparks/la-trb-six-flags-magic-mountain-roller-coasters-01201117,0,5604411.story|work=LA Times|date=January 18, 2011}}</ref> Due to Green Lantern being placed in Gotham City Backlot, the area was re-themed into DC Universe. In addition, Grinder Gearworks became \"Wonder Woman: Lasso Of Truth\" and Atom Smasher was renamed \"The Flash: Speed Force\".\n\nIn August 2011, several [[News media (United States)|media sources]] reported that [[Six Flags New England]] would install Six Flags Magic Mountain's ''D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu'' for the park's [[Giant Inverted Boomerang|2012 season]].<ref name=\"MassLive.com\">{{cite web|last=Constantine|first=Sandra|title=Six Flags New England working to add new roller coaster ride to its Agawam amusement park|url=http://www.masslive.com/news/index.ssf/2011/08/six_flags_working_to_add_a_new.html|work=News Article|publisher=MassLive.com|date=August 16, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"New Coaster\">{{cite web|last=Hagist|first=Jenna|title=Six Flags Adds New Coaster|url=http://www.wggb.com/story/15294563/six-flags-adds-new-coaster|work=News Article|publisher=Wggb.com|date=August 18, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002155826/http://www.wggb.com/story/15294563/six-flags-adds-new-coaster|archivedate=October 2, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"LAT Review\">{{cite news|last=MacDonald|first=Brady|title=Six Flags Magic Mountain to remove Deja Vu coaster|url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/deals/themeparks/la-trb-deja-vu-six-flags-new-england-08201119,0,2637256.story?track=rss&dlvrit=70653|accessdate=August 19, 2011|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=August 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn September 1, 2011, Six Flags Magic Mountain announced that they would be opening a new attraction for the 2012 season named [[Lex Luthor: Drop of Doom]]. The free-fall drop attraction was integrated into both sides of the park's {{Convert|415|ft}} tall [[Superman: Escape from Krypton]] tower structure and ranks as the world's tallest drop tower, featuring a plummet from {{Convert|400|ft|m}} above ground level. The following day, Six Flags Magic Mountain confirmed on Facebook that D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu would be removed from the park.<ref name=\"Deja Vu removal\">{{cite web|title=Hey D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu fans!...|url=http://www.facebook.com/SixFlagsMagicMountain/posts/10150359136147125|author=Six Flags Magic Mountain|publisher=Facebook|date=September 2, 2011|accessdate=September 4, 2011}}</ref> Then on September 13, 2011, the park announced that D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu would be removed after October 16, 2011, \"D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu fans, we have created some exclusive after hours ride time for you to ride it again before October 16.\"<ref name=\"Deja Vu date\">{{cite web|title=D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu fans...|url=http://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10150372377677125&set=a.111563082124.115580.67502107124&type=1&theater|author=Six Flags Magic Mountain|publisher=Facebook|date=September 13, 2011|accessdate=September 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, 2011, [[Log Jammer (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Log Jammer]] was partially removed to open up space for [[Full Throttle (roller coaster)|Full Throttle]], which opened in 2013.\n\nIn August 2012, Six Flags Magic Mountain confirmed rumors that a new roller coaster, [[Full Throttle (roller coaster)|Full Throttle]], would open the following season. Full Throttle opened as the park's 18th roller coaster, allowing Six Flags Magic Mountain to market having the most roller coasters in the world once again. The ride was built to feature the world's tallest vertical loop on a roller coaster at {{convert|160|ft}}. In addition, Full Throttle set a record for being the first roller coaster to feature a track section with rails on both sides of the spine. This occurs at the top of the ride's massive inversion.<ref name=\"Full Throttle Review\">{{cite web|title=Screamscape.com|url=http://www.screamscape.com/html/six_flags_magic_mountain.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130704102521/http://www.screamscape.com/html/six_flags_magic_mountain.htm#2013|archivedate=2013-07-04|author=Screamscape|publisher=Screamscape|date=June 24, 2013|accessdate=July 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn August 29, 2013, Six Flags Magic Mountain officially announced that they would run both Batman: The Ride and Colossus backwards for a limited time of the 2014 season. They will also expand Bugs Bunny World with the addition of a new roller coaster.<ref>{{cite web |title=New for 2014 |url=http://content.sixflags.com/comingin2014/ |date=August 29, 2013 |accessdate=August 29, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130901054320/http://content.sixflags.com/comingin2014/ |archivedate=September 1, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref> On April 8, 2014, Six Flags Magic Mountain announced that the park will host its first ever ''[[Holiday in the Park]]'' Christmas event in late 2014 and for future years after.<ref name=\"SFMM\">{{cite web|title=Six Flags Magic Mountain Lights Up the Season by Introducing Holiday in the Park\u00ae Event\n|url=https://www.sixflags.com/magicmountain/newsroom/holiday-in-the-park-announcement|author=Six Flags Magic Mountain|publisher=Six Flags|date=April 8, 2014|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2014, the park placed banners across the property advertising the Bonzai Pipelines in the adjacent property, [[Six Flags Hurricane Harbor|Hurricane Harbor]], along with the closing of Colossus which took place on August 16, 2014.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=Park_Journey|author=Park Journey|number=473515920690642944|date=2 June 2014|title=Here you go. Confirmation of #IronColossus at @SFMagicMountain? Thanks to  @knotts_network for the pic.}}/photo/1</ref>  On August 28, 2014, Six Flags announced the [[Rocky Mountain Construction]] conversion of Colossus into [[Twisted Colossus]]. Twisted Colossus opened on May 23, 2015.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.latimes.com/travel/themeparks/la-trb-twisted-colossus-six-flags-magic-mountain-20140828-story.html | title = Six Flags Magic Mountain turning wooden coaster into Twisted Colossus | first = Brady | last = MacDonald | date = August 28, 2014 | work = [[Los Angeles Times]] | access-date = February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn September 3, 2015, Six Flags announced the renovation of [[The New Revolution (roller coaster)|Revolution]] with a new paint scheme, upgraded lighting, and new train eliminating the controversial over-the-shoulder restraints that had been the source of the ride's spotty reputation for much of its life. Named \"The New Revolution,\" the roller coaster reopened on April 21, 2016.\n\nOn September 1, 2016, the park announced [[Justice League: Battle for Metropolis]] to open in 2017. The 4D shooting dark ride is nearly identical to the [[Justice League: Battle for Metropolis|six other installations]] located at Six Flags parks around North America. The ride opened on July 12, 2017 and is located in the Metropolis section near The Riddler's Revenge.<ref name= JusticeLeagueBattle>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SFMagicMountain/status/880244450626199552|title=Just Announced! JUSTICE LEAGUE: Battle for Metropolis opens to the public on July 12! Who's ready to Join the League!? #JusticeLeaguepic.twitter.com/aEbm9uAPsA|last=MM|first=Six Flags|date=2017-06-28|website=@SFMagicMountain|language=en|access-date=2017-09-16}}</ref>\n\nOn August 29, 2017, Six Flags announced the addition of a [[Zamperla]] Giant Discovery flat ride to be built in a newly renovated Boardwalk Beach area near DC Universe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sixflags.com/national/new-for-2018|title=New for 2018 {{!}} National|website=National|language=en|access-date=2017-09-16}}</ref> Marketed as \"the world's tallest pendulum ride\", CraZanity takes riders to a height of 172 feet (52.4 m) and speeds up to 75&nbsp;mph (120.7 kmh).<ref>{{cite news|title=World\u2019s Tallest Pendulum Ride, CraZanity, at Six Flags Magic Mountain in 2018 - Now 365 Days of Thrills|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20170831005368/en/World%E2%80%99s-Tallest-Pendulum-Ride-CraZanity-Flags-Magic|date= August 31, 2017|work=Business Wire}}</ref>\n\nOn August 29, 2018, the park announced the brand new racing launch coaster [[West Coast Racers]] from [[Premier Rides]] and a revamp of the old Cyclone Bay area into a high energy, urban [[Los Angeles]]. The ride itself is dubbed the first launched racing coaster in the world and the first quadruple launched coaster, even though the existing [[Fiorano GT Challenge]] holds these records. The M\u00f6bius loop coaster officially opened to the public on January 9, 2020, and became the 19th coaster at the park.\n\nOn March 24, 2019, the park announced that [[Green Lantern: First Flight (roller coaster)|Green Lantern: First Flight]] would permanently close and be removed from the park which no longer makes West Coast Racers the park's 20th coaster.<ref>https://www.coaster101.com/2019/03/24/six-flags-magic-mountain-to-remove-green-lantern/</ref><ref>https://www.themeparkinsider.com/flume/201903/6676/</ref>\n\n==Themed areas==\nThere are presently eleven separately themed areas within the park \u2013 each zone featuring its own distinct rides, attractions, and food service venues.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"|Area\n! class=\"unsortable\" |  Picture\n! Description\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|DC Universe\n| {{N/A|}}\n|The rides and attractions in this area are inspired by the DC comics universe.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|Screampunk District\n| {{N/A|}}\n|Carnival-style games, and three of the park's largest roller coasters. Also features Lex Luthor: Drop of Doom.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|Bugs Bunny World\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM Magic Flyer.jpg|150px]]\n|Feature rides and attractions inspired by Looney Tune characters. This area also contains Whistlestop Park. There are four Junior roller coasters. Originally Thomas Town, you can see that the trains in Bugs Bunny World are just repaints of the original Thomas characters.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|Full Throttle Plaza\n| {{N/A|}}\n|Extreme lifestyle inspired, this area features an outdoor barbecue, sit-down sports bar, gift shop, splash pad, and concerts. Full Throttle is the main attraction of this area.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|Six Flags Plaza \n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Six Flags Plaza.JPG|150px]]\n|The main entry and exit of the park.  Features gift shops, food service venues, photo services, and guest relations.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|Baja Ridge\n| {{N/A|}}\n|South of the border themed desert landscape; includes X\u00b2 and Viper.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|Rapids Camp Crossing\n| {{N/A|}} [[File:SFMM- Roaring Rapids 1.JPG|150px]]\n|This area simulates a campsite set deep in the American wilderness. The main attraction of this area is the Roaring Rapids. Although not camping themed, the entrance to Tatsu is included in this area.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|The Underground\n| {{N/A|}}\n|A newly renovated area for 2019 that features Apocalypse, West Coast Racers, Jet Stream, and Cyclone 500; among others. Previously known as Cyclone Bay.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|Metropolis\n| {{N/A|}}\n|The rides and attractions in this area are inspired by the Justice League of the DC comics universe. The main attractions are Justice League: Battle for Metropolis & The Riddler's Revenge.<ref name=\"JusticeLeagueBattle\" />\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|Samurai Summit\n| {{N/A|}} [[File:SFMM- Superman Shuttle Coaster.jpg|150px]]\n|Japanese folklore and mythology themed area, with two roller coasters atop its rugged hillside. Superman: Escape from Krypton, though not Japanese themed, is included in this area.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|The Boardwalk\n| {{N/A|}}\n|A newly renovated area for 2018 that features CraZanity, Gold Rusher, Scrambler, Jammin' Bumpers, and Tidal Wave.<ref>{{cite news |last=Barrera |first=Sandra |date=February 20, 2018 |title=This is what Six Flags Magic Mountain\u2019s newest thrill ride building site looks like right now |url=https://www.dailynews.com/2018/02/20/this-is-what-six-flags-magic-mountains-newest-thrill-ride-building-site-looks-like-right-now/ |work=Los Angeles Daily News |location=Los Angeles, California |access-date=April 10, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Cinema, television, and computer games==\n<!-- This should not include every single listing of every appearance. Please keep to major, notable releases. -->\nMagic Mountain's proximity to downtown Los Angeles, the hub of the American film and television industry, has resulted in its appearance in several productions, usually representing a park other than itself. The debut of ''Revolution'' was the focal point of the 1977 release ''[[Rollercoaster (1977 film)|Rollercoaster]]''. [[Bob Einstein]], as his character [[Super Dave Osborne]], performed his first \"stunt\" on a rollercoster at Magic Mountain. In 1983, Magic Mountain became the fictional \"Walley World\" for ''[[National Lampoon's Vacation]]'', with scenes featuring ''Revolution'' and ''Colossus'' (each using fictional names). On television, Magic Mountain doubled as the theme park in the opening credits of the television series ''[[Step by Step (TV series)|Step by Step]]''. Other TV productions featuring Magic Mountain have included: [[NCIS (franchise)|NCIS]], ''[[Entourage (U.S. TV series)|Entourage]]'',  ''[[The Bionic Woman]]'', ''[[The A-Team]]'', ''[[CHiPs]]'', ''[[Wonder Woman (TV series)|Wonder Woman]]'', ''[[Way Out Games]]'', ''[[Knight Rider (1982 TV series)|Knight Rider]]'', ''[[Beverly Hills, 90210]]'', ''[[Melrose Place]]'', ''[[The King of Queens]]'', and ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer (TV series)|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]''. The band [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] also filmed their acting debut in 1978's [[made-for-TV]] ''[[Kiss Meets the Phantom of the Park]]'' that featured the band members in the park and near Colossus.  In the 2000 movie ''[[Space Cowboys]]'' Donald Sutherland is shown riding Viper and is portrayed as the designer when Clint Eastwood recruits him.\n\nMagic Mountain was also the filming site for the [[Real Wheels]] video, \"Here Comes A Roller Coaster\", as well as for the ''[[Kidsongs]]'' 1990 video, \"Ride the Roller Coaster\".\n\nIn the [[Nickelodeon]] show ''[[Drake & Josh]]'', Drake, Josh, and Megan take a trip to Mystic Mountain (parody of Magic Mountain) in the episode \"The Demonator\", and they ride the \"Demonator\". On ''[[Zoey 101]]'' Zoey and Lisa take Michael to Mystic Mountain (both series were created by [[Dan Schneider (TV producer)|Dan Schneider]]), and they help Michael overcome his roller coaster fear in the episode \"Rollercoaster\". He rides the \"Spine Twister\", which was actually the [[Goliath (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Goliath]] from Magic Mountain. In 1990, Nickelodeon's ''[[Wild and Crazy Kids]]'', the wooden roller coaster,Colossus, was featured as a game called \"Wacky RollerCoaster Spill\". In the movie ''[[This Is Spinal Tap]]'', the band performs as second billing to a puppet show at the fictional \"Themeland Amusement Park\" in [[Stockton, California]], located {{convert|300|mi|km}} north of Santa Clarita. The actual filming location is Magic Mountain's amphitheater. The [[Kidsongs]] video ''Ride the Roller Coaster'' is set at Six Flags Magic Mountain. Nick Cannon group ''[[The School Gyrls]]'' movie premiere was at Magic Mountain. In the film ''[[Judy Moody and the Not Bummer Summer]]'', they go to a theme park and ride a roller coaster for the first time. The coaster was Goliath. Goliath was also featured as the \"Aquaman\" roller coaster in the third season of the [[HBO]] series ''[[Entourage (U.S. TV series)|Entourage]]''.\n\nIn 2011, the park was chosen as the setting for the [[Travel Channel]]'s version of the quiz show ''[[Scream! If You Know the Answer]]''. The ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' cast visited the park in 2012 for their senior skip day in the \"[[Big Brother (Glee)|Big Brother]]\" episode, where they ride [[Viper (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Viper]].<ref name=\"Glee\">{{cite web|title=Six Flags Magic Mountain has a cameo appearance ...|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10150799927722125&set=a.111563082124.115580.67502107124&type=1|author=Six Flags Magic Mountain|publisher=Facebook|date=April 10, 2012|accessdate=April 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, a large section of the parking lot was blocked off for a Toyota Camry commercial. Both pictures and the background footage reveal Goliath and Colossus, indicating that it is Magic Mountain where the commercial was shot. The ride that was built for the commercial bears a resemblance to the park's new coaster at the time, Full Throttle: a big hill, a barrier-test loop, a backwards propulsion section, and a forwards propulsion section that runs through a tunnel placed next to the hill.<ref name=\"ToyotaCommercial\">{{cite web | url=http://www.thecoasterguy.com/index.php/2013/10/01/toyota-camry-thrill-ride-six-flags-magic-mountain/ | title=Toyota Camry Thrill Ride At Six Flags Magic Mountain | work=thecoasterguy.com | date=1 October 2013 | accessdate=19 February 2014 | author=Dahlin, Kurt}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Goliath was used for a [[Carpool Karaoke]] segment with Selena Gomez.\n\nIn 2017, the park was used in Katy Perry's music video \"Chained to the Rhythm\".\n\nIn 2017, areas of the park were used in the filming of the Netflix comedy film, ''[[Sandy Wexler]]'' starring [[Adam Sandler]].\n\nAlthough not featured, Magic Mountain is mentioned numerous times in the Netflix horror-comedy  ''[[Santa Clarita Diet]]''.\n\nA recreation of Six Flags Magic Mountain was featured built in the computer game [[RollerCoaster Tycoon 2]], also including a blank version of the park with no rides and attractions.\n\n==Attractions==\n===Roller coasters===\nSix Flags Magic Mountain holds the record for most roller coasters in an amusement park at 19.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n! Current Name\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Picture\n! style=\"width:7%;\"| Year opened\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Manufacturer\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Park area\n! style=\"width:5%;\"|Thrill/intensity rating\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Description\n|-\n| [[Apocalypse: The Ride]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Apocalypse 2.JPG|150px]]\n| 2009\n| [[Great Coasters International]]\n| The Underground\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Wooden roller coaster featuring steeply banked turns and twisting drops.\nKnown in the past as \"Terminator Salvation: The Ride\" (2009\u20132010)\n|-\n| [[Batman: The Ride]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:Batman signage.JPG|150px]]\n| 1994\n| [[Bolliger & Mabillard]]\n| DC Universe\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| A cloned inverted coaster that whips around steeply banked turns and five inversions.\n|-\n| [[Canyon Blaster (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Canyon Blaster]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:Canyon Blaster rollercoaster, Six Flags Magic Mountain, Valencia, California - 20071228.jpg|150px]]\n| 1999\n| [[E&F Miler Industries]]\n| Bugs Bunny World\n| Mild\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Junior roller coaster.\n|-\n| [[Full Throttle (roller coaster)|Full Throttle]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Full Throttle 2.JPG|150px]]\n| 2013\n| [[Premier Rides]]\n| Full Throttle Plaza\n| Maximum\n| align=\"left\" | A launch roller coaster with 2 forward launches and one backwards launch. Full Throttle has one of the world's tallest [[vertical loop]]s at {{Convert|160|ft}} and the first ever \"top hat\" constructed on an inversion. \n|-\n| [[Goldrusher|Gold Rusher]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Gold Rusher 2.JPG|150px]]\n| 1971\n| [[Arrow Development]]\n| BoardWalk\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Riders dip, turn, and dive up and around the park's mountainous terrain. Gold Rusher is Six Flags Magic Mountain's first roller coaster.\n|-\n| [[Goliath (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Goliath]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:Goliath at Six Flags Magic Mountain (first drop).jpg|150px]]\n| 2000\n| [[Giovanola]]\n| Goliath Plaza\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Riders brave an opening drop of {{convert|255|ft|m}} into a subterranean tunnel and multiple steep banking turns. \n|-\n| [[Magic Flyer (roller coaster)|Magic Flyer]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:Six Flags Magic Mountain children area.jpg|150px]]\n| 1971\n| Bradley and Kaye\n| Bugs Bunny World\n| Mild\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|Train themed Junior roller coaster in Whistlestop Park.\nKnown in the past as \"Goliath Jr.\" (2001\u20132007) and \"Percy's Railway\" (2008\u20132010)\n|-\n| [[Ninja (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Ninja]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:Ninja loading.jpg|150px]]\n| 1988\n| [[Arrow Dynamics]]\n| Samurai Summit\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Swinging coaches suspended from an overhead steel track whip around steeply banked turns and curves in and out of the treetops.\n|-\n| [[The New Revolution (roller coaster)|The New Revolution]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- New Revolution 1.jpg|150px]]\n| 1976\n| [[Anton Schwarzkopf]]\n| Baja Ridge\n| Moderate (Maximum with VR Goggles.)\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Riders careen through steep banking turns and spirals in and out of the treetops.  Revolution has a full 360 degree loop which is the first modern vertical loop in the world. In 2016 the coaster received a major renovation which included: new trains, lapbars, new paint job, new lighting, reduced foliage and VR Goggles were added to intensify the ride.\n|-\n| [[The Riddler's Revenge]] \n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Riddler's Revenge 1.JPG|150px]]\n| 1998\n| [[Bolliger & Mabillard]]\n| Metropolis\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Upon opening, it was the tallest, fastest, longest stand-up coaster in the world. Riders traverse six inverted turns over the course of its {{convert|4370|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} track.\n|-\n| [[Road Runner Express (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Road Runner Express]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:Road Runner Express - Six Flags Magic Mountain.JPG|150px]]\n| 2011\n| [[Vekoma]]\n| Bugs Bunny World\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Junior roller coaster.\n|-\n| [[Scream (roller coaster)|Scream]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM-_Scream.jpg|150px]]\n| 2003\n| [[Bolliger & Mabillard]]\n| Screampunk District\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Floorless trains riding above the rails traverse seven inversions on {{convert|3985|ft|m}} of steel track.\n|-\n| Speedy Gonzales Hot Rod Racers\n|{{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Speedy Gonzales Roller Coaster.jpg|150px]]\n| 2014\n| [[Zamperla]]\n| Bugs Bunny World\n| Mild\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Race-car themed [[Zamperla]] family gravity coaster with helix.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hometownstation.com/santa-clarita-news/arts-and-entertainment/magic-mountain/six-flags-magic-mountain-announces-new-ride|title=Six Flags Magic Mountain Announces New Ride Speedy Gonzales Hot Rod Racers|publisher=KHTS AM 1220|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221205236/http://hometownstation.com/santa-clarita-news/arts-and-entertainment/magic-mountain/six-flags-magic-mountain-announces-new-ride|archivedate=February 21, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Superman: Escape from Krypton]] \n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM-Superman Escape from Krypton.JPG|150px]]\n| 1997\n| [[Intamin]]\n| Samurai Summit\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | First coaster to reach 100&nbsp;mph. Riders accelerate in reverse from 0 to {{convert|104|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} in seven seconds and climb nearly 41 stories into the air. Entrance to Superman: Escape from Krypton, a launch roller coaster. Known in the past as \"Superman: The Escape\" (1997\u20132010).\n|-\n| [[Tatsu]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:Six Flags Magic Mountain Tatsu2.jpg|150px]]\n| 2006\n| [[Bolliger & Mabillard]]\n| Samurai Summit\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Upon opening, Tatsu was the tallest, fastest, and longest flying roller coaster in the world. Suspended beneath a steel track, riders experience a total of {{convert|263|ft}} in elevation changes while harnessed in a prone position. It also features the world's largest pretzel loop.\n|-\n| [[Twisted Colossus]]\n|{{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Twisted Colossus.jpg|150px]]\n| 2015\n| [[Rocky Mountain Construction]]\n| Screampunk District\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Riders experience steep drops, banking curves, and two inversions on nearly {{convert|5,000|ft|m}} of track - designed to pit two simultaneously operating trains in a race against each other. It is also the world's longest racing coaster.\n|-\n| [[Viper (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Viper]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Viper.JPG|150px]]\n| 1990\n| [[Arrow Dynamics]]\n| Baja Ridge\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{convert|188|ft|m}} tall with seven inversions reaching speeds up to {{convert|70|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}\n\n|- \n| [[West Coast Racers]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:Six Flags Magic Mountain - 49256408391.jpg|150px]]\n| 2020\n| [[Premier Rides]]\n| The Underground\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Quadruple launch racing coaster, In partnership with [[West Coast Customs]].\n|-\n| [[X2 (roller coaster)|X\u00b2]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:X2-firstdrop.jpg|150px]]\n| 2002\n| [[Arrow Dynamics]]\n| Baja Ridge\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Riders experience predetermined forward and reverse somersaulting maneuvers while harnessed in seats that pitch on a separate axis from the track. Known in the past as \"X\" (2002\u20132007). It was the world's first 4D coaster.\n|}\n\n===Other attractions===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n! Ride\n! Picture\n! style=\"width:7%;\"| Year Introduced\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Manufacturer\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Location in Park\n! style=\"width:5%;\"|Thrill/Intensity Rating\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Description\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Buccaneer\n| {{N/A|}} [[File:SFMM- Buccaner.jpg|150px]]\n| 1980\n| [[Intamin]]\n| Goliath Plaza\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align