system. Known from 2001\u20132006 as Arrowhead Splashdown. Jet Stream is a family friendly flume ride located near the entrance to Gold Rusher. The ride opened in 1972.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Justice League: Battle for Metropolis]]\n| {{N/A|}} [[File:SFMM- Justice League Battle for Metropolis.jpg|Justice League Battle for Metropolis|150px]]\n| 2017\n| [[Sally Corporation]]\n| Metropolis\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align;\"| An interactive 4D shooting family dark ride.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Lex Luthor: Drop of Doom]]\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:Lex Luthor, Drop of Doom - Six Flags Magic Mountain.JPG|150px]]\n| 2012\n| [[Intamin]]\n| Screampunk District  \n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Free fall drop thrill ride from a height of {{convert|400|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}, attaining a terminal velocity of {{convert|85|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. It was the tallest drop tower until 2014 when Zuminjaro: Drop of Doom opened.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Honda Express\n| {{N/A|}}[[File:SFMM- Orient Express.JPG|150px]]\n| 1971\n| Korneuberg Shipbuilding Company ([[Austria]])\n| Six Flags Plaza / Samurai Summit\n| Mild\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{RailGauge|1000mm|allk=on}}<ref>{{Cite web|title=Trams of the World 2017|url=http://blickpunktstrab.net/wordpress2/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/tramsderwelt2017.pdf|publisher=Blickpunkt Stra\u00dfenbahn|date=January 24, 2017|accessdate=February 16, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216202427/http://blickpunktstrab.net/wordpress2/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/tramsderwelt2017.pdf|archivedate=February 16, 2017}}</ref> [[funicular]] railway ride, which transports guests to Samurai Summit next to Ninja.  Repainted in 2016 to blue/white in conjunction with Honda sponsorship. Previously known from 1988 - 2016 as Orient Express and from 1971\u20131988 as ''Funicular''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecoasterguy.com/index.php/2011/10/17/ride-profile-orient-express/|title=Ride Profile: Orient Express|author=Kurt Dahlin|accessdate=February 8, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Roaring Rapids]]\n| [[File:SFMM- Roaring Rapids 2.JPG|150px]]\n| 1981\n| [[Intamin]]\n| Rapids Camp Crossing \n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Rapids water attraction simulating a wilderness raft expedition. Roaring Rapids at Six Flags Magic Mountain. Many guests claim it is the best water ride at the park.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Jammin' Bumpers\n| {{N/A|}}\n| 1971\n| [[Reverchon]]\n| BoardWalk\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Bumper cars.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Scrambler\n| [[File:SFMM- Scrambler.JPG|150px]]\n| 2003\n| [[Eli Bridge]]\n| BoardWalk\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| The park's former old Scrambler was damaged from an uprooted tree. This Scrambler was relocated from [[Six Flags Over Texas]].\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Sling Shot\n| {{N/A|}}\n| 2012\n| [[Funtime (manufacturer)|Funtime]]\n| The Underground\n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Sling Shot extra charge attraction.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Swashbuckler\n| [[File:SFMM- Swashbucker.jpg|150px]]\n| 1983\n| [[Chance Rides]]\n| Goliath Plaza \n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Chance Yo-Yo attraction.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Tidal Wave (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Tidal Wave]] \n| [[File:SFMM- Tidal Wave 02.JPG|150px]]\n| 1989\n| [[Intamin]]\n| BoardWalk\n| Moderate\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Shoot-the-Chute]] flume. Goes under a bridge on which people get soaked. Tidal Wave is a Shoot the Chute water ride which features a {{convert|50|ft|m|1|adj=on}} drop. The ride is labeled by Six Flags Magic Mountain as a family friendly ride.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|CraZanity \n| [[File:SFMM- Crazinity.jpg|Crazanity|150px]]\n| 2018\n| [[Zamperla]]\n| BoardWalk \n| Maximum\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| A Zamperla Giga Discovery. Pendulum ride. {{convert|172|ft|m}} high. {{convert|75|mph|km/h}}. Tallest pendulum ride in the world.\n|}\n\n==Former rides & attractions==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:16%;\"|Ride\n! style=\"width:7%;\"|Year Opened\n! style=\"width:7%;\"|Year Closed\n! style=\"width:20%;\"|Manufacturer\n! style=\"width:65%;\"|Description\n|-\n|99 Steam Train\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1981\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Crown Metal Products]]\n|The {{RailGauge|2ft|lk=on}} [[Narrow gauge railway|narrow gauge]] train ride to Trollywood, the troll country.<ref>[http://www.steamlocomotive.com/lists/searchdb.php?str=Calgrove+Kennels&country=USA Surviving Steam Locomotive Search - Calgrove Kennels]</ref>\n|-\n|Billy the Squid\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1973\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Anton Schwarzkopf]]\n|[[Octopus (ride)|Polyp Ride]]. In 1973 this Polyp ride had a maintenance problem and was removed. The Jolly Monster was built on its site.\n|-\n|Circus Wheel\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1999\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Chance Rides]]\n|Chance [[Wipeout (ride)|Trabant]] with Roman theming. It spun in a clockwise direction and tilted at the same time. The Trabant was removed and replaced with a Tilt-A-Whirl, retaining the Circus Wheel name.\n|-\n|Circus Wheel\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1981\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2008\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Sellner Manufacturing]]\n|This Sellner [[Tilt-A-Whirl]] was known in the past under the names Fiesta Dance 1981-1981; Baile de las Flores 1982\u20131988 and Jolly Roger 1988\u20131999. The Tilt-A-Whirl was removed to make room for 3-Point Challenge basketball game, which was replaced by CraZanity. Tilt-A-Whirl has been in storage in a boneyard.\n|-\n|[[Twisted Colossus|Colossus]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1978\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2014\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[International Amusement Devices]]\n|The iconic wooden coaster, which had two tracks, was redesigned in August 2014 as Twisted Colossus, a converted hybrid coaster. \n|-\n|Condor\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1988\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1989\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Huss Rides]]\n|This Huss Condor was open for two years before being removed. It was removed to make room for Viper.\n|-\n|Crazy Barrels\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1989\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|This Intamin Drunken Barrels was formerly located at a county fair. The Barrels were removed when the ride closed in 1989 and the platform for where the ride used to be was demolished in late 2017.\n|-\n|[[Goliath (Boomerang)|D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2001\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2011\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Vekoma]]\n|Located in \"Cyclone Bay\". A Floorless coaches suspended beneath an overhead track traverse the track forward and in reverse. Removed and the coaster was sent to ''[[Six Flags New England]]'' as ''Goliath''.\n|-\n|Dragon\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1974\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1981\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow Development]]\n|This transportation [[cable railway]] transported riders from the upper level of the back of the mountain down to the lower level, and vice versa. The ride ceased operation in 1981 but was not removed until Ninja was built in 1988. Parts of the upper station were reused for Ninja, The Dragon's concrete track, wall, and lower station are visible to the left of Ninja's final lift hill.\n|-\n|Eagle's Flight \u2013 El Dorado\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1981\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|This Intamin aerial sky-way ride took passengers from the upper part of the mountain to the lower land on the north of the mountain. The station was next to El Bumpo's area.\n|-\n|Eagle's Flight \u2013 Galaxy\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1994\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|A second aerial sky-way ride from the top of the mountain to the lower land in the County Fair area.\n|-\n|El-Bumpo\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1979\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow Development]]\n|Gas-powered bumper boats located on the pond.\n|-Enterprise\n|[[Flashback (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Flashback]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1992\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2008\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|Steel roller coaster featuring a stacked design and numerous steep rolling track dives. The Flashback was standing but not operating starting in 2003 and demolished and scrapped in 2008.\n|-\n|Freefall\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1982\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2008\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|An Intamin 1st-generation Freefall. The ride was standing but not operating from 2005 to 2006; however, it was scrapped for the 2008 season.\n|-\n|{{Anchor|Galaxy}}Galaxy<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20140223114829/http://www.vintagedisneylandtickets.com/images/MM1971a.jpg</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1979\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|{{nowrap|Astron International Corporation}}\n|A Robinson double Ferris wheel with cable pulley that looked like a V-shaped beam. The ride was removed and was located where Buccaneer and Swashbuckler are now sitting. It was relocated to [[California's Great America]] and then later removed.\n|-\n|Grand Centennial Excursion Railroad\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1975\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1985\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|\n|A {{RailGauge|3ft|lk=on}} narrow gauge<ref>[https://pcrailroad.wordpress.com/2007/01/27/a-history-of-no-1/ Pacific Coast Railroad Company - A History of No. 1]</ref> steam train that took passengers around. Located north of the main mountain.\n|-\n|Granny Gran Prix\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2007\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Morgan Manufacturing|D. H. Morgan]]\n|This track-guided car ride was known as Chevron Gran Prix (Gas Powered) from 1971\u20131986. A new turnpike (electric-powered) was opened for three years before being moved in 1988 to Bugs Bunny World. The old guided track was demolished to make room for Tidal Wave. In December 2007 it was demolished to make room for Thomas Town's opening in 2008.\n|-\n\n|[[Green Lantern: First Flight (roller coaster)|Green Lantern: First Flight]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2011\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2017\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|A 4th Dimension roller coaster which was the first ZacSpin model in the United States and the second at the park following [[X2 (roller coaster)|X2]] from [[Arrow Dynamics]]. Removed in 2019 and the coaster will reopen at La Ronde as Vip\u00e8re in 2020 <ref>https://www.sixflags.com/larondeen/newfor2020</ref> \n|-\n|Jolly Monster\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1973\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1981\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|Eyerly\n|A standard Eyerly Monster ride which replaced Billy the Squid. This thrill ride was at the Pirate's Cove near Colossus, Buccaneer, and Swashbuckler. The ride was removed and its site sat empty for 7 years before the Tilt-A-Whirl was moved there.\n|-\n|Little Sailor Ride\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1985\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|\n|Yankee Doodle Dandy (1971\u20131972) Sailboat Ride (1973\u20131980) Little Sailor Ride (1981\u20131985)\n|-\n|[[Log Jammer (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Log Jammer]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2011\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Arrow Dynamics|Arrow Development]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Log flume featuring two large drops. Removed to make way for Full Throttle.\n|-\n|Magic Pagoda\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1974\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1984\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|\n|A walk-thru attraction located on Samurai Summit. It featured a talking Buddha, a mirror maze, a strobe light room (with a dragon flying overhead), a walk through a miniature version of Chinatown and various other small scale items of interest with a Chinese Theme. Now used as part of a walk-through maze for the Halloween season.\n|-\n|Metro\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2011\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|Universal Mobility\n|This monorail ride ran three stations; one at the High Sierra Territory (Demolished, now serves as Reds Revenge Haunted Maze during Frightfest), one at the Colossus County Fair (Demolished in 2017 to make room for the CraZanity Pendulum ride) and one at Samurai Summit (this station is currently used as the launch tunnel for Full Throttle). The monorail had been standing but not operating since 2001 and it was announced by Six Flags in 2007 that the ride would have no plans to reopen. The trains were located near the former location of Flashback where they sat for 10 years. In 2011 the monorail trains are relocated to [[Hersheypark]]. The abandoned track has been taken down in all areas readily visible to parkgoers but sections of track still exist and may be glimpsed in heavily overgrown sections of the park such as the area behind Buccaneer and Swashbuckler.\n|-\n|Mountain Express\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1973\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1982\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Anton Schwarzkopf]]\n|Wildcat coaster located near where Flashback stood. Relocated to Magic Landing as Wildcat and then to Bosque Magico as Montana Rusa.\n|-\n|[[Psyclone (roller coaster)|Psyclone]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1991\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2006\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Dinn Corporation]]\n|A wood tracked roller coaster patterned after the Cyclone at Astroland park in Brooklyn, New York. It was torn down for the 2007 season, and piles of wood remained at the site for many days after the destruction. The site is now home to another wooden coaster, Apocalypse.\n|-\n|Reactor\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1977\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1993\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Anton Schwarzkopf]]\n|A Schwarzkopf Enterprise, known from 1977\u20131987 as Enterprise, was renamed Reactor in 1987. This thrill ride was removed at the end of the 1993 season.\n|-\n|[[La Vibora|Sarajevo Bobsleds]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1984\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1986\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|Bobsled coaster named after the 1984 Olympics. Removed due to the Six Flags ride rotation program and replaced with Shockwave. It was moved to Six Flags Over Texas and opened as Avalanche, but was later renamed and rethemed as La Vibora to better match the Spain section of the park.\n|-\n|Scrambler\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1973\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2003\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Eli Bridge]]\n|This scrambler had a lot of damage from an uprooted tree and was scrapped; however, Six Flags Magic Mountain received another scrambler from Six Flags Over Texas.\n|-\n|[[Batman The Escape|Shockwave ]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1986\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1988\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|A Steel Standup looping roller coaster. it was removed in 1989 and relocated to Six Flags Great Adventure due to the ride rotation program.\n|-\n|Sierra Twist\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1973\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2008\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Anton Schwarzkopf]]\n|A Schwarzkopf [[Bayern Kurve]] ride, originally known as Swiss Twist. It was a high-speed bobsled ride with a circular track. The ride was removed due to aging parts and high maintenance costs.\n|-\n|Spin Out\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1971\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2008\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Chance Rides]]\n|A [[Rotor (ride)|Chance Rotor]] known from 1971\u20131972 as Bottoms Up. Featured in the video for [[Belinda Carlisle]]'s No. 1 hit song, \"Heaven is a Place on Earth\" \n|-\n|Thrill Shot\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2001\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2012\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[S&S Worldwide]]\n|Rapidly ascending slingshot attraction. The ride requires a nominal fee from guests to participate. Thrill Shot closed in 2009 and never reopened due to high maintenance costs. In early 2012, Thrill Shot was removed.\n|-\n|Tumble Drum\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1974\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1980\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|\n|This walk-through barrel roll was located near the Electric Rainbow (Round up ride).\n|-\n|Yosemite Sam Sierra Falls\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1993\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|2010\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|WhiteWater West Industries\n|Double tube waterslides with dingy raft on location at the Bugs Bunny World. Demolished to make room for Road Runner Express.\n|-\n|Z-Force\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1987\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|1993\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Intamin]]\n|An Intamin Looping Starship/Space Shuttle themed as an Air Force fighter plane. The ride was removed at the end of the season in 1993 to make room for [[Batman: The Ride]].\n|}\n\n==Rankings==\n[[File:SFMM- Riddlers Revenge.JPG|thumb|The Riddler's Revenge, the world's tallest and fastest stand-up roller coaster featuring six inversions.]]\n[[File:SFMM- Full Throttle 1.JPG|thumb|Full Throttle is a launch roller coaster which features the world's second highest vertical loop at {{convert|160|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}.]]\nSix Flags Magic Mountain's coasters are commonly ranked high in Amusement Today's annual [[Golden Ticket Awards]]. With the opening of Full Throttle on June 22, 2013, Six Flags Magic Mountain obtained the world record for the largest number of roller coasters in an amusement park.\n\nBelow is a table with roller coasters at Six Flags Magic Mountain and their highest ranking in the Golden Ticket Awards.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.goldenticketawards.com/pdfs/at_goldenticket_2012_web.pdf|title=Amusement Today&nbsp;\u2014 Golden Ticket Winners 2012|format=PDF|magazine=Amusement Today|accessdate=September 10, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120919232328/http://www.goldenticketawards.com/pdfs/at_goldenticket_2012_web.pdf|archivedate=September 19, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Roller Coaster\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Highest Rank\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[X\u00b2 (roller coaster)|X\u00b2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Tatsu]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|28\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Goliath (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Goliath]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Twisted Colossus]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Full Throttle (roller coaster)|Full Throttle]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|39\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[The Riddler's Revenge]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|39\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Batman: The Ride]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Apocalypse: The Ride]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|27\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Scream (roller coaster)|Scream]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|52\n|-\n|}\n\n===Record breaking rides===\nSix Flags Magic Mountain has several attractions that set world records in various categories.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Ride\n!align=\"left\"|Type of ride\n!align=\"left\"|Opening Date\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Record(s)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Height\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[The New Revolution (roller coaster)|The New Revolution]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Steel roller coaster]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|May 8, 1976\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |First [[vertical loop]]ing roller coaster built since 1901.<ref name=\"Coney Island History\">{{cite web|last=Sandy|first=Adam|title=Coney Island History|url=http://www.ultimaterollercoaster.com/coasters/history/early_1900/coney_island.shtml|work=Roller Coaster History|publisher=Ultimate Roller Coaster|accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref>  World's tallest roller coaster when it opened to the public.<ref name=\"Revolution34\">{{cite news|last=William-Ross|first=Lindsay|title=You Say You Want a Revolution? Magic Mountain's Turns 34 Today|url=http://laist.com/2010/05/08/you_say_you_want_a_revolution_magic.php|accessdate=3 July 2013|newspaper=LAist|date=8 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618221208/http://laist.com/2010/05/08/you_say_you_want_a_revolution_magic.php|archivedate=June 18, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|113|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Superman: Escape from Krypton]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Shuttle roller coaster]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Superman: The Escape: March 15, 1997\nSuperman: Escape from Krypton; March 19, 2011\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|One of the world's first 2 roller coasters to reach 100&nbsp;mph.\nFirst roller coaster to reach {{convert|400|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}. becoming the world's tallest coaster until 2003.\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|415|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[The Riddler's Revenge]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Stand-up roller coaster]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|April 4, 1998\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|World's tallest, longest & fastest stand-up roller coaster.\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|156|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Goliath (Six Flags Magic Mountain)|Goliath]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Steel roller coaster\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|February 11, 2000\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|World's longest & fastest initial drop ({{convert|255|ft|m|0|abbr=on|disp=or}}) on a closed-circuit coaster until May 13, 2000.\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|235|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[X\u00b2 (roller coaster)|X\u00b2]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[4th Dimension roller coaster]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|X: January 12, 2002 ; X\u00b2: May 24, 2008\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |World's first [[4th dimension roller coaster]].\nFeatures flipping seats, chainlift music, fog and fire.\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|175|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Tatsu]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Flying roller coaster]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|May 13, 2006\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|World's tallest, fastest & longest flying coaster. Features world's biggest pretzel loop.\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|170|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Lex Luthor: Drop of Doom]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Drop tower]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|July 7, 2012\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|World's tallest tower drop ride when it opened in 2012. Its record was broken by [[Zumanjaro: Drop of Doom]] in 2014.\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|400|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Full Throttle (roller coaster)|Full Throttle]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Launched roller coaster]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|June 22, 2013\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|First launched roller coaster featuring \"top hat\" constructed on a vertical loop. World's highest vertical loop when built.\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|160|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|CraZanity\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Pendulum ride]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|July 13, 2018\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|World's Tallest Pendulum Ride\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{convert|172|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Greater Los Angeles}}\n\n* [[Incidents at Six Flags parks]]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage|Magic Mountain}}\n* {{official website|http://www.sixflags.com/magicMountain/}}\n* {{RCDB|4532}}\n{{Six Flags}}\n{{Six Flags Magic Mountain}}\n{{Amusement Parks & Theme Parks of California}}\n{{Santa Clara River}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Six Flags Magic Mountain}}\n[[Category:Six Flags Magic Mountain| ]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks in