|archivedate=January 27, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nHe played for [[CS Sedan Ardennes|Sedan]], [[Angers SCO|Angers]], [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]], [[SM Caen|Caen]], [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]], [[A.C. Monza Brianza 1912|Monza]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/players/fran-players-in-it.html |title=French Players in Italy |website=Rsssf.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-25}}</ref> [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tfc.info/wiki/saison-1998-1999 |title=L'histoire du club par saison &#124; Le site officiel du Toulouse Football Club |language=fr |website=Tfc.info |date= |accessdate=2016-01-25}}</ref> [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] and [[Persma Manado]].{{refn|{{LFP|id=fernandez-joachim}}}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dundee United FC Season 2000-01]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fernandez, Joachim}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:French footballers]]\n[[Category:Senegalese footballers]]\n[[Category:CS Sedan Ardennes players]]\n[[Category:Angers SCO players]]\n[[Category:FC Girondins de Bordeaux players]]\n[[Category:Stade Malherbe Caen players]]\n[[Category:Udinese Calcio players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Monza players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Milan players]]\n[[Category:Toulouse FC players]]\n[[Category:Dundee United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 2 players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:French people of Senegalese descent]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n\n\n{{Senegal-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add totalcaps and totalgoals.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joachim_Fernandez"}
{"title_page": "Willem Weertman", "text_new": "'''Willem Weertman''' is an [[United States|American]] engineer known for his work as an engineer at [[Chrysler]] Corporation, where he was actively involved in the creation of many of the company's most famous engines, including the [[Chrysler Slant-6 engine|Slant Six]], [[Chrysler K engine|2.2 four]], and [[Chrysler LA engine|LA V8 (318, 360)]].  He graduated from [[Yale University]] with a bachelor of engineering degree in 1947 before joining the Chrysler Institute of Engineering; in 1949 he started work at the Plymouth Assembly Plant before spending 1950\u20131952 with the Navy in the [[Korean War]]. In 1954 Weertman became the first resident engineer for the Plymouth Mound Road V8 engine plant, which started producing A-engines in 1955. In December 1955, Weertman was promoted up to the Engine Design Department of Chrysler's Central Engineering department and assigned a title of Manager - Engine Design. In this capacity he worked on the [[Chrysler B engine]] and [[Chrysler Slant-6 engine|Slant Six]], which would become known for its durability and at the time was considered to have high performance for its size. Valiants powered by this engine took first through seventh place in the first and only NASCAR sanctioned compact-car race.<ref>{{cite web|title=The slant six Hyper-Pak|author=\"Jerry Engle\"|url=http://www.allpar.com/mopar/hyper-pak.html|accessdate=2008-05-29}}</ref>\n\nAfter the success of these engines, Weertman was promoted to Assistant Chief Engineer-Engine Design. He worked on the successful adaptation of the [[Chrysler A engine]] to a new lightweight casting design, which incorporated other improvements as well, and was designed the [[Chrysler LA engine]]; this series was made from 1964 through 1993, with a major redesign during those years resulting in SMPI \"Magnum\" engines which continued until 2002, while a racing engine based on the design is still made, as is the derivative V-10 all-alloy engine which is in every [[Dodge Viper]] to this day. An iron V-10 was available for HD pickup trucks, filling in for the B and RB engines which were discontinued after 1978. Weertman also had a major influence on the overhead valve straight-six engines made and sold in Australia known as the [[Chrysler Hemi-6 Engine|Hemi Six]] Originally destined for US light truck duty (which never happened), these engines were designed primarily for performance and light weight; a Valiant Charger equipped with the largest of the Hemi Sixes was actually faster than the same car powered by a larger V8 engine, and set a local-production acceleration record that endured until 1988.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chrysler Valiants, Valiant Chargers, Valiant Pacers, and other cars of Chrysler Australia|url=http://valiant.org/ausval.html|accessdate=2008-05-29}}</ref>\n\nFollowing this, Weertman was promoted to Chief Engineer - Engine Design and Development, a position which he held until retirement. From this point he worked mainly on four cylinder engines, as well as a V6 adaptation of the successful LA design for the [[Dodge Dakota]]. Willem Weertman retired from Chrysler Corporation after forty years but remained active, producing a 400-page book covering every engine made by Chrysler from 1922 until the company was taken over in 1998, \"Chrysler Engines 1922-1998,\" published by the Society of Automotive Engineers.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Relevant Links==\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Weertman\n  | first = Willem\n  | title = Chrysler Engines 1922-1998\n  | publisher = SAE International\n  | year = 2008\n  | location = Warrendale, PA\n  | pages = 419\n  | isbn = 978-0-7680-1642-0}}\n*  {{cite web|title=Willem Weertman - Chrysler engine creator - personal and engine chronology|publisher=Allpar|url=http://www.allpar.com/corporate/bios/weertman-chron.html|accessdate=2008-05-29}}\n* {{cite web|title=Willem Weertman - Chrysler Chief Engineer, Engine Design and Development (Interview)|publisher=allpar|url=http://www.allpar.com/corporate/bios/weertman.html|accessdate=2008-05-29}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weertman, Willem}}\n[[Category:Chrysler executives]]\n[[Category:21st-century American engineers]]\n[[Category:People in the automobile industry]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "'''Willem Weertman''' is an [[United States|American]] engineer known for his work as an engineer at [[Chrysler]] Corporation, where he was actively involved in the creation of many of the company's most famous engines, including the [[Chrysler Slant-6 engine|Slant Six]], [[Chrysler K engine|2.2 four]], and [[Chrysler LA engine|LA V8 (318, 360)]].  He graduated from [[Yale University]] with a bachelor of engineering degree in 1947 before joining the Chrysler Institute of Engineering; in 1949 he started work at the Plymouth Assembly Plant before spending 1950-1952 with the Navy in the [[Korean War]]. In 1954 Weertman became the first resident engineer for the Plymouth Mound Road V8 engine plant, which started producing A-engines in 1955. In December 1955, Weertman was promoted up to the Engine Design Department of Chrysler's Central Engineering department and assigned a title of Manager - Engine Design. In this capacity he worked on the [[Chrysler B engine]] and [[Chrysler Slant-6 engine|Slant Six]], which would become known for its durability and at the time was considered to have high performance for its size. Valiants powered by this engine took first through seventh place in the first and only NASCAR sanctioned compact-car race.<ref>{{cite web|title=The slant six Hyper-Pak|author=\"Jerry Engle\"|url=http://www.allpar.com/mopar/hyper-pak.html|accessdate=2008-05-29}}</ref>\n\nAfter the success of these engines, Weertman was promoted to Assistant Chief Engineer-Engine Design. He worked on the successful adaptation of the [[Chrysler A engine]] to a new lightweight casting design, which incorporated other improvements as well, and was designed the [[Chrysler LA engine]]; this series was made from 1964 through 1993, with a major redesign during those years resulting in SMPI \"Magnum\" engines which continued until 2002, while a racing engine based on the design is still made, as is the derivative V-10 all-alloy engine which is in every [[Dodge Viper]] to this day. An iron V-10 was available for HD pickup trucks, filling in for the B and RB engines which were discontinued after 1978. Weertman also had a major influence on the overhead valve straight-six engines made and sold in Australia known as the [[Chrysler Hemi-6 Engine|Hemi Six]] Originally destined for US light truck duty (which never happened), these engines were designed primarily for performance and light weight; a Valiant Charger equipped with the largest of the Hemi Sixes was actually faster than the same car powered by a larger V8 engine, and set a local-production acceleration record that endured until 1988.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chrysler Valiants, Valiant Chargers, Valiant Pacers, and other cars of Chrysler Australia|url=http://valiant.org/ausval.html|accessdate=2008-05-29}}</ref>\n\nFollowing this, Weertman was promoted to Chief Engineer - Engine Design and Development, a position which he held until retirement. From this point he worked mainly on four cylinder engines, as well as a V6 adaptation of the successful LA design for the [[Dodge Dakota]]. Willem Weertman retired from Chrysler Corporation after forty years but remained active, producing a 400-page book covering every engine made by Chrysler from 1922 until the company was taken over in 1998, \"Chrysler Engines 1922-1998,\" published by the Society of Automotive Engineers.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Relevant Links==\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Weertman\n  | first = Willem\n  | title = Chrysler Engines 1922-1998\n  | publisher = SAE International\n  | year = 2008\n  | location = Warrendale, PA\n  | pages = 419\n  | isbn = 978-0-7680-1642-0}}\n*  {{cite web|title=Willem Weertman - Chrysler engine creator - personal and engine chronology|publisher=Allpar|url=http://www.allpar.com/corporate/bios/weertman-chron.html|accessdate=2008-05-29}}\n* {{cite web|title=Willem Weertman - Chrysler Chief Engineer, Engine Design and Development (Interview)|publisher=allpar|url=http://www.allpar.com/corporate/bios/weertman.html|accessdate=2008-05-29}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weertman, Willem}}\n[[Category:Chrysler executives]]\n[[Category:21st-century American engineers]]\n[[Category:People in the automobile industry]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1950-1952 \u2192 1950\u20131952", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willem_Weertman"}
